             = Isernia, Cattedrale di San Pietro Apostolo, facciata.jpg\n| image_size        =  \n| image_alt         = \n| caption           = Cathedral of [[Isernia]]\n<!---- Locations ---->\n| country           = {{flag|Italy}}\n| metropolitan      =  \n| territory         = \n| province          = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Campobasso-Boiano|Campobasso-Boiano]]\n| coordinates       = <!-- Use {{coord}} --> \n<!---- Statistics ---->\n| area_km2          = 740 \n| population        = 63,000\n| population_as_of  = 2006\n| catholics         = 60,000<!-- Number of Catholics in the diocese -->\n| catholics_percent = 95.2\n| parishes          = 48<!-- Number of parishes in the diocese -->\n| churches          = <!-- Number of churches in the diocese -->\n| congregations     = <!-- Number of congregations in the diocese -->\n| schools           = <!-- Number of church supported schools in the diocese -->\n| members           = <!-- Number of members in the diocese -->\n<!---- Information ---->\n| denomination      = [[Catholic Church]]\n| rite              = [[Roman Rite]]\n| established       = 5th Century \n| cathedral         = [[Isernia Cathedral|Cattedrale di S. Pietro Apostolo]] (Isernia)\n| cocathedral       = Concattedrale di S. Maria Assunta (Venafro)\n| patron            = \n| priests           = <!-- Number of priests in the diocese -->\n<!---- Current leadership ---->\n| pope              = {{Incumbent pope}} <!-- DO NOT CHANGE. This will update the Popes Automatically as they change -->\n| bishop_title      = Bishop\n| bishop            = Vacant see ([[Sede vacante]]); Bishop [[Salvatore Visco]] was appointed Archbishop of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Capua]] on Tuesday, April 30, 2013, by [[Pope Francis]] \n| coadjutor         = \n| auxiliary_bishops = \n| vicar_general     = \n| emeritus_bishops  = [[Andrea Gemma]], [[Sons of Divine Providence|F.D.P.]]\n<!---- Map ---->\n| map               = \n| map_alt           = \n| map_caption       = \n<!---- Website ---->\n| website           = [http://www.iserniavenafro.net/ www.iserniavenafro.net]\n| footnotes         = \n}}\nThe Italian Catholic '''diocese of [[Isernia]]-Venafro''' ({{lang-la|Dioecesis Aeserniensis-Venafrensis}}) in [[Molise]], is a [[suffragan]] of the [[archdiocese of Campobasso-Boiano]]. In 1852 the historic '''diocese of Isernia''' was combined with the '''diocese of Venafro''', to form the '''diocese of Isernia e Venafro'''.<ref name=CathHierDioIseVena>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/disve.html \"Diocese of Isernia-Venafro\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David m. Cheney. Retrieved January 30, 2016</ref><ref name=GCathIseVena>[http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/iser0.htm \"Diocese of Isernia-Venafro\"] ''GCatholic''. Gabriel Chow. Retrieved January 30, 2016</ref> The seat of the present bishop is [[Isernia Cathedral]], while [[Venafro Cathedral]] has become a [[co-cathedral]] in the new diocese.\n\n\n==History==\nAfter the Lombard invasions Isernia was the seat of a countship, founded by the [[Duke of Benevento]]. It was destroyed by the Saracens in the ninth century, and in 1199 was sacked by [[Marcolvaldo]], the vicar of the deceased [[Emperor Henry VI]]. In 1805 it was visited by [[1805 Molise earthquake|a severe earthquake]], which ruined the ancient cathedral.\n\nThe epoch of the saintly Bishop Benedict is doubtful, though the existence of the episcopal see in the fifth century is certain. \n\nIn 1032 the Diocese of Venafro (formerly the seat of Roman country residences), which had its own bishops from the fifth century, was united to Isernia, and in 1230 it was again separated.\n\n==Bishops==\n===Diocese of Isernia===\n''Erected: 5th Century'' \n\n*[[Cristoforo Maroni]] (1387 \u2013 18 Dec 1389 Appointed, Cardinal-Priest of San Ciriaco alle Terme Diocleziane) \n;''...''\n*[[Carlo Setari]] (12 Jan 1470 \u2013 1486 Died)<ref name=HierarchiaII-Isernia>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/hierarchiacathol02eubeuoft#page/168/2up|first=Konrad|last=Eubel|authorlink=Konrad Eubel|title=Hierarchia catholica medii et recentioris aevi |volume=Vol. II|pages=169|date=1914|publisher=Libreria Regensbergiana|location=M\u00fcnster|edition=second|ISBN=}} ''(in Latin)''</ref>\n*[[Francesco Adami]] (10 Apr 1486 \u2013 1497 Died)<ref name=HierarchiaII-Isernia />\n*[[Costantino Castriota detto Scanderbeg]] (2 Oct 1497 \u2013 1500 Died)<ref name=HierarchiaII-Isernia />\n*[[Giovanni Olivieri]] (8 Apr 1500 \u2013 1510 Died)<ref name=HierarchiaII-Isernia /><ref name=HierarchiaIII-Isernia>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/hierarchiacathol03eube#page/214/mode/2up|first=Konrad|last=Eubel|authorlink=Konrad Eubel|title=Hierarchia catholica medii et recentioris aevi |volume=Vol. III|pages=214|date=1923|publisher=Libreria Regensbergiana|location=M\u00fcnster|edition=second|ISBN=}} ''(in Latin)''</ref>\n*[[Massimo Bruni Corvino]] (30 Sep 1510 \u2013 1522 Died)<ref name=HierarchiaIII-Isernia />\n*[[Christopher Numar of Forli]], [[O.F.M. Obs.]] (17 Apr 1523 \u2013 19 Dec 1524 Resigned)<ref name=HierarchiaIII-Isernia /> \n*[[Antonio Numai]] (19 Dec 1524 \u2013 1567 Resigned)<ref name=HierarchiaIII-Isernia /> \n*[[Giovanni Battista Lomellino]] (17 Mar 1567 \u2013 22 Nov 1599 Died)<ref name=HierarchiaIII-Isernia /> \n*[[Paolo De Curtis]], [[Theatines|C.R.]] (15 Mar 1600 \u2013 1606 Resigned)<ref name=HierarchiaIV>{{cite book|url=http://sul-derivatives.stanford.edu/derivative?CSNID=00002719&mediaType=application/pdf|last1=Gauchat|first1=Patritius (Patrice)|title=HIERARCHIA CATHOLICA MEDII ET RECENTIORIS AEVI Vol IV|pages=211|publisher=|date=|ISBN=}}</ref><ref name=CathHierPaoCurt>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bdcurtis.html \"Bishop Paolo De Curtis, C.R.\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David M. Cheney. Retrieved November 24, 2016</ref>\n*[[Alessio Geromoaddi]] (24 Apr 1606 \u2013 6 Apr 1611 Died)<ref name=HierarchiaIV /> \n*[[Marcantonio Genovesi]] (26 Sep 1611 \u2013 7 Nov 1624 Died)<r