iari]].<ref>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/digle.html ''Catholic Encyclopedia'' page]</ref><ref name=CathHierIglesias>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/digle.html \"Diocese of Iglesias\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David M. Cheney. Retrieved April 24, 2017</ref><ref name=GCathIglesias>[http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/igle0.htm \"Diocese of Iglesias\"] ''GCatholic.org''. Gabriel Chow. Retrieved April 24, 2017</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{context|date=October 2016}}\nThe [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Sulcis|Diocese of Sulci]] was an episcopal seat as early as the seventh century. After its decline the bishop of Sulci took up his residence at the village of [[Tratalias]];<ref>[http://www.sardegne.com/sardinia-info/architecture-and-museums/churches/610-hundreds-of-churches-scattered-in-the-territory-of-sulcis-iglesiente.html Hundreds of churches scattered in the territory of Sulcis-Iglesiente \u2013 Sardinia churches \u2013 Sardegne.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> in 1503 the seat was officially moved to [[Iglesias, Sardinia|Iglesias]] but in 1514 the Diocese was reunited with the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Cagliari|Archdiocese of Cagliari]]\n\nIn 1763 the see was re-established, and [[Luigi Satta]] appointed bishop. \n[[File:Tratalias cattedrale.jpg|thumb|right|Tratalias cathedral]]\nThe cathedral of Iglesias (then ''Villa di Chiesa'') was erected by the [[Pisa]]ns in 1285, but has been restored in later times.<ref>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/07638b.htm ''Catholic Encyclopedia'' article]</ref> The previous cathedral located in Tratalias was built in a [[Pisa]]n-[[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] style between 1213 and 1282.\n\n==Bishops==\n*Luigi Satta (1763\u20131772 Died)\n*Giovanni Ignazio Gautier (1772\u20131773 Died)\n*Francesco Antonio Deplano (1775\u20131781 Died)\n*Giacinto Francesco Rolfi, [[O.E.S.A.]] (1783\u20131789 Died)\n*Giuseppe Domenico Porqueddu (1792\u20131799 Died)\n*Nicolo Navoni (1800\u20131819 Confirmed, [[Archbishop of Cagliari]])\n*Giovanni Nepomuceno Ferdiani (1819\u20131841 Died)\n*Raimondo Orr\u00f9 (1842\u2013Did Not Take Effect)\n*Giovanni Stephano Masala (1842\u2013Did Not Take Effect)\n*Giovanni Battista Montixi (1844\u20131884 Died)\n*Raimondo Ingheo-Ledda (1884\u20131907 Resigned)\n*Giuseppe Dallepiane (1911\u20131920 Died)\n*Saturnino Peri (1920\u20131929 Resigned)\n*Giovanni Pirastru (1930\u20131970 Retired)\n*Giovanni Cogoni (1970\u20131992 Retired)\n*Arrigo Miglio (1992\u20131999 Appointed, [[Bishop of Ivrea]])\n*Tarcisio Pillolla (1999\u20132007 Retired)\n*Giovanni Paolo Zedda (8 Mar 2007 \u2013 )\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{Catholic}}\n\n{{Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of Cagliari}}\n\n{{coord|39.3167|N|8.5333|E|source:wikidata-and-enwiki-cat-tree_region:IT|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses in Sardinia|Iglesias]]\n[[Category:Religious organizations established in 1763]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses and prelatures established in the 18th century|Davenport]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roman_Catholic_Diocese_of_Iglesias"}
{"title_page": "Jewish Museum of Belgium shooting", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title            = {{nowrap|Jewish Museum of Belgium shooting}}\n| partof           = [[Terrorism in Belgium]] and [[Islamic terrorism in Europe (2014\u2013present)]]\n| image            = Bruxelles rue des Minimes 21.jpg\n| image_size       = 200px\n| alt              = \n| caption          = {{nowrap|The Jewish Museum of Belgium, pictured in 2009}}\n| map              = \n| map_size         = \n| map_alt          = \n| map_caption      = \n| location         = [[Jewish Museum of Belgium]]<br />[[Brussels]], [[Belgium]]\n| target           = \n| coordinates      = \n| date             = {{Start date|2014|05|24|df=y}}\n| time             = 15:47 [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| timezone         = [[UTC+02:00]]\n| type             = [[Mass shooting]]\n| fatalities       = 4\n| injuries         = \n| victims          = \n| perpetrators     = Mehdi Nemmouche<br>Nacer Bendrer (co-author)\n| susperp          = \n| weapons          = [[Zastava M70|Zastava M70AB]] <small>(semi-automatic rifle)</small><br>[[Llama firearms|Llama Scorpio]] <small>([[.38 Special|.38-caliber]] revolver)</small>\n| numparts         = \n| dfens            = \n| motive           = [[Islamic extremism]], [[antisemitism]]\n| convictions      = Nemmouche: life imprisonment<br>Bendrer: 15 years imprisonment\n}}\nOn 24 May 2014, a gunman opened fire at the [[Jewish Museum of Belgium]] in [[Brussels]], killing four people. Three died at the scene; a fourth was taken to the hospital and died on 6 June. On 30 May 2014, Mehdi Nemmouche, a 29-year-old [[France|French]] national of [[Algeria]]n origin, was arrested at [[Marseille]] in connection with the shooting. He is believed to have spent over a year in Syria and had links with radical Islamists.\n\n==Shooting==\nA man wearing a cap, carrying several bags and armed with a handgun and a [[Kalashnikov rifle]] arrived at the [[Jewish Museum of Belgium]], near the [[Sablon (Brussels)|Sablon]] in central Brussels, at around half past three.<ref name=gm>{{cite news|last=Casert|first=Raf|title=Belgium ramps up security for lone suspect in Jewish Museum attack|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/police-hunt-brussels-jewish-museum-shooter-france-tightens-security/article18835439/|archive-url=https://archive.is/20140527190719/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/police-hunt-brussels-jewish-museum-shooter-france-tightens-security/article18835439/|url-status=dead|archive-date=27 May 2014|accessdate=26 May 2014|newspaper=The Globe and the Mail|date=25 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lesoir.be/559864/article/actualite/belgique/2014-06-01/fusillade-au-musee-juif-bruxelles-un-francais-arrete|accessdate=6 June 2014|newspaper=[[Le Soir]]|date=1 June 2014|title=Fusillade au Mus\u00e9e juif de Bruxelles: un Fran\u00e7ais arr\u00eat\u00e9|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140604201419/http://www.lesoir.be/559864/article/actualite/belgique/2014-06-01/fusillade-au-musee-juif-bruxelles-un-francais-arrete|archive-date=4 June 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> He then opened fire, killing three people on site and critically wounding a fourth, who was soon taken to hospital<ref name=\"JP\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/Report-Israeli-couple-among-Brussels-Jewish-museum-shooting-victims-353251 |title=Report: Israeli couple among Brussels Jewish museum shooting victims |newspaper=The Jerusalem Post |date=25 May 2014 |accessdate=25 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525035315/http://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/Report-Israeli-couple-among-Brussels-Jewish-museum-shooting-victims-353251 |archive-date=25 May 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> and who died of his injuries on 6 June.<ref name=\"fourthvictim\">{{cite news|url=http://www.demorgen.be/dm/nl/30966/Schietpartij-aan-Joods-Museum-in-Brussel/article/detail/1910854/2014/06/06/Vierde-slachtoffer-aanslag-Joods-museum-overleden.dhtml|title=Vierde slachtoffer aanslag Joods museum overleden|date=6 June 2014|publisher=[[De Morgen]]|accessdate=6 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728223443/http://www.demorgen.be/dm/nl/30966/Schietpartij-aan-Joods-Museum-in-Brussel/article/detail/1910854/2014/06/06/Vierde-slachtoffer-aanslag-Joods-museum-overleden.dhtml|archive-date=28 July 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The attack lasted less than 90 seconds,<ref>{{cite news|title=Federaal parket gaat uit van terreuraanslag|url=http://www.hln.be/hln/nl/30962/Schietpartij-aan-Joods-Museum-in-Brussel/article/detail/1899346/2014/05/26/Federaal-parket-gaat-uit-van-terreuraanslag.dhtml|accessdate=27 May 2014|newspaper=[[Het Laatste Nieuws]]|date=26 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527020019/http://www.hln.be/hln/nl/30962/Schietpartij-aan-Joods-Museum-in-Brussel/article/detail/1899346/2014/05/26/Federaal-parket-gaat-uit-van-terreuraanslag.dhtml|archive-date=27 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> after which the shooter fled the scene on foot<ref name=gm /><ref name=\"Captured Jewish Museum shooting suspect carried weapons, gas mask\">{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/06/01/world/europe/france-belgium-jewish-shooting/ |title=Captured Jewish Museum shooting suspect carried weapons, gas mask |publisher=CNN |date=2 June 2014 |accessdate=29 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714233938/http://www.cnn.com/2014/06/01/world/europe/france-belgium-jewish-shooting |archive-date=14 July 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> and was partially captured by security cameras.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27567396|title=Belgian police in appeal to public over gunman identity|work=BBC News Online|accessdate=26 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525235650/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27567396|archive-date=25 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> According to police, he headed into a different part of downtown Brussels before disappearing.<ref name=\"Captured Jewish Museum shooting suspect carried weapons, gas mask\" /> According to security camera footage, the attacker appeared to wear a baseball-type cap covering-up his head, and a chest-mounted camera, like [[Mohammed Merah]], who filmed his acts during the 2012 [[Toulouse and Montauban shootings]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lalibre.be/actu/belgique/fusillade-a-bruxelles-le-parquet-qualifie-les-faits-de-terroristes-5382d19a35704f05d69d576a|work=[[La Libre Belgique|La Libre]]|date=26 May 2014|trans-title=Shooting in Brussels: prosecutors call the acts \"terrorism\"|language=fr|title=Fusillade \u00e0 Bruxelles: le parquet qualifie les faits de \"terroristes\"|access-date=27 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140528010605/http://www.lalibre.be/actu/belgique/fusillade-a-bruxelles-le-parquet-qualifie-les-faits-de-terroristes-5382d19a35704f05d69d576a|archive-date=28 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> although it was stated that the camera failed during filming.<ref name=\"Captured Jewish Museum shooting suspect carried weapons, gas mask\" /><ref name=\"Suspect in Jewish museum killings claimed responsibility in video\">{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2014/06/01/frenchman-suspected-ties-to-syria-jihadists-reportedly-arrested-in-connection/ |title=Suspect in Jewish museum killings claimed responsibility in video |publisher=Fox News |date=1 June 2014 |accessdate=29 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140705190438/http://www.foxnews.com/world/2014/06/01/frenchman-suspected-ties-to-syria-jihadists-reportedly-arrested-in-connection/ |archive-date=5 July 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe Belgian Minister of Foreign Affairs, [[Didier Reynders]], happened to be in the vicinity of the museum and heard the gunshots. The Minister of the Interior, [[Jo\u00eblle Milquet]], was also nearby and arrived on the scene a few minutes later.<ref name=\"MuseumAttack\"/>\n\n=== Victims ===\nFour people were killed in the shooting. Two of the victims were [[Israelis]], Emanuel and Miriam Riva, a middle-aged couple on holiday from [[Tel Aviv]], while a French woman named Dominique Sabrier was the third victim.\n\nA young Belgian man who worked at the museum, Alexandre Strens, was critically wounded<ref name=\"MuseumAttack\">{{cite news|title=Belgian police hunt gunman after Jewish museum murders|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/may/25/belgian-police-hunt-gunman-jewish-museum-murders-brussels|accessdate=25 May 2014|newspaper=The Guardian|agency=[[Agence France-Presse]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525221420/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/may/25/belgian-police-hunt-gunman-jewish-museum-murders-brussels|archive-date=25 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> and died of his wounds on 6 June. He was born in Morocco to a Jewish mother and [[Algeria]]n [[Berber people|Berber]] father, and his body was returned to [[Taza, Morocco]], for burial in a Muslim cemetery.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.english.rfi.fr/africa/20140610-fourth-victim-brussels-jewish-museum-killings-buried-muslim-cemetery-morocco |title=Fourth victim of Brussels Jewish Museum killings buried in Moroccan Muslim cemetery |publisher=[[Radio France Internationale]] |date=10 June 2014 |accessdate=16 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140615120222/http://www.english.rfi.fr/africa/20140610-fourth-victim-brussels-jewish-museum-killings-buried-muslim-cemetery-morocco |archive-date=15 June 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27733876|date=6 June 2014|title=Brussels Jewish Museum killings: Fourth victim dies|access-date=21 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180916160533/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27733876|archive-date=16 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://moroccantimes.com/2014/06/morocco-25-year-old-alexander-strens-buried-taza/ |title=Morocco: 25-Year-Old Alexander Strens to be buried in Taza |publisher=The Moroccan Times |date=9 June 2014 |accessdate=16 June 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140617034434/http://moroccantimes.com/2014/06/morocco-25-year-old-alexander-strens-buried-taza/ |archivedate=17 June 2014 }}</ref>\n\n== Investigation ==\nA nationwide manhunt was launched for the attacker, who was described as being of medium height and athletic build, and wearing a dark baseball cap. His image, partly obscured, was captured on [[Closed-circuit television|CCTV]]. A man who was seen driving from the museum was detained, but released after questioning, and remains a witness in the investigation.<ref name=\"ShootingSuspect\">{{cite news|title=Belgian police in appeal to public over gunman identity|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27567396|accessdate=19 June 2013|publisher=BBC|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525191330/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27567396|archive-date=25 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Deputy prosecutor Ine Van Wymersch said the shooter \"probably acted alone, was armed and well prepared.\" She stated that the motive for the attack was still \"open\".<ref name=\"news.nationalpost.com\">{{cite web |url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2014/05/25/photos-of-jewish-museum-shooter-released-as-belgium-launches-nationwide-manhunt-for-suspect-who-killed-four/ |title=Photos of Jewish Museum shooter released as Belgium launches manhunt for suspect who killed four &#124; National Post |publisher=News.nationalpost.com |date= |accessdate=29 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729081256/http://news.nationalpost.com/2014/05/25/photos-of-jewish-museum-shooter-released-as-belgium-launches-nationwide-manhunt-for-suspect-who-killed-four/ |archive-date=29 July 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> The attack was being investigated as a terrorist incident.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/europeennes-2014/article/2014/05/26/tueur-du-musee-la-belgique-choisit-une-juridiction-competente-en-matiere-de-terrorisme_4426217_4350146.html|date=26 May 2014|work=[[Le Monde]]|trans-title=Killings at the Belgian Jewish museum treated as \"terrorism\"|title=La tuerie du Mus\u00e9e juif de Bruxelles qualifi\u00e9e d'acte \" terroriste \"|access-date=29 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529223426/http://www.lemonde.fr/europeennes-2014/article/2014/05/26/tueur-du-musee-la-belgique-choisit-une-juridiction-competente-en-matiere-de-terrorisme_4426217_4350146.html|archive-date=29 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Perpetrator ===\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name = Mehdi Nemmouche\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = Mehdi Nemmouche\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1985|04|17|df=yes}} \n| birth_place = [[Roubaix]], [[France]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| nationality = [[France|French]], [[Algeria]]n\n| other_names = \n| criminal_charge = [[Robbery]] (2007) <br /> [[Murder]] (2014)\n| penalty = 5 years imprisonment (2007) <br /> Life in prison (2019)\n| conviction_status = Tried and found guilty\n| allegiance = \n| motive = [[Antisemitism]], [[Islamism]]\n| conviction = [[Robbery]] (2007), [[Murder]] (2019)\n| date =\n| time = \n| locations = \n| targets = \n| fatalities = \n| apprehended = 30 May 2014\n}}\n\n'''Mehdi Nemmouche''' ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u0647\u062f\u064a \u0646\u0645\u0648\u0634}}; born 17 April 1985), a 29-year-old French citizen, was arrested on 30 May 2014 at the [[Gare Saint-Charles (Marseille)|Saint-Charles]] railway station in [[Marseille]] in connection with the shooting. Nemmouche is suspected to have returned to France from [[Foreign rebel fighters in the Syrian Civil War|fighting for Islamist rebels]] in the [[Syrian Civil War]] in 2013.<ref name=\"BBC suspect\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27654505|title=Brussels Jewish Museum killings: Man held in Marseille|date=1 June 2014|work=BBC News|accessdate=1 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140601084139/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27654505|archive-date=1 June 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> He appears{{clarify|reason=Did he or didn't he + says who?|date=September 2017}} to have recorded a video bearing the flag of the rebel group [[Islamic State in Iraq and Syria]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/europe/article/2014/06/01/tuerie-de-bruxelles-un-suspect-francais-arrete_4429835_3214.html|title=Pourquoi Mehdi Nemmouche est le principal suspect de la tuerie de Bruxelles|date=1 June 2014|trans-title=Why Mehdi Nemmouche is the principal suspect of the killings in Brussels|language=fr|access-date=16 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140614151109/http://www.lemonde.fr/europe/article/2014/06/01/tuerie-de-bruxelles-un-suspect-francais-arrete_4429835_3214.html|archive-date=14 June 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nNemmouche was born in [[Roubaix]]. His father abandoned his mother before he was born and he was raised primarily by his grandmother and in group homes. Prior to leaving for Syria, he already had a long criminal history, including arrests for armed robbery, vehicle theft, and vandalism. He reportedly told hostages in Syria he was planning an attack in Paris on [[Bastille Day]].<ref name=lemonde>{{cite web|title=Mehdi Nemmouche: ce que l'on sait de son parcours|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/societe/article/2014/09/08/mehdi-nemmouche-ce-que-l-on-sait-de-son-parcours_4483458_3224.html|website=lemonde.fr|publisher=[[Le Monde]]|accessdate=10 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151121102022/http://www.lemonde.fr/societe/article/2014/09/08/mehdi-nemmouche-ce-que-l-on-sait-de-son-parcours_4483458_3224.html|archive-date=21 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nNemmouche had previously spent five years in prison where he is suspected to [[Islamist radicalization in European prisons|have been radicalized]].<ref name=BisserbeRadicalization>{{cite news|last1=Bisserbe|first1=Noemie|title=European Prisons Fueling Spread of Islamic Radicalism|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/european-prisons-fueling-spread-of-islamic-radicalism-1470001491|accessdate=23 August 2016|website=[[the Wall Street Journal]]|date=31 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160823000615/http://www.wsj.com/articles/european-prisons-fueling-spread-of-islamic-radicalism-1470001491|archive-date=23 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> He left for Syria only three weeks after being released from prison in September 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=Captured Jewish Museum shooting suspect carried weapons, gas mask|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/06/01/world/europe/france-belgium-jewish-shooting|date=2 June 2014|publisher=[[CNN]]|accessdate=2 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140604074132/http://edition.cnn.com/2014/06/01/world/europe/france-belgium-jewish-shooting|archive-date=4 June 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> If proven guilty, he will be the first European volunteer in the Syrian war who committed attacks upon returning to Europe.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mulholland|first=Rory|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/france/10868197/French-police-arrest-Syria-Jihadist-over-Brussels-Jewish-Museum-murders.html|title=French police arrest Syria jihadist over Brussels Jewish Museum murders|newspaper=Telegraph|date=1 June 2014|accessdate=29 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140721130618/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/france/10868197/French-police-arrest-Syria-jihadist-over-Brussels-Jewish-Museum-murders.html|archive-date=21 July 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> A number of items were recovered from a bag he was carrying while being detained, including a [[Kalashnikov rifle]], a [[.38 Special]] [[revolver]], nearly 330 rounds of ammunition for both weapons, gun parts, cameras, clothing, and a [[gas mask]]. A hidden file containing a 40-second video was discovered in one of the cameras; in it, Nemmouche's weapons are recorded and a voice, believed to belong to Nemmouche by police, claimed responsibility for the museum shooting in an audio commentary.<ref name=\"Captured Jewish Museum shooting suspect carried weapons, gas mask\"/><ref name=\"Suspect in Jewish museum killings claimed responsibility in video\"/> He was said to have had a white sheet emblazoned with the name of the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]].<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27660683|title=France arrests Syria jihad suspects as Nemmouche held|date=2 June 2014|work=BBC News|access-date=21 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180914035038/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27660683|archive-date=14 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nNemmouche, who has Algerian as well as French citizenship, resisted extradition to Belgium.<ref name=\"RTL\">{{cite web|author=Staff|url=http://www.rtl.be/info/belgique/faitsdivers/1097831/mehdi-nemmouche-sort-du-silence-je-suis-solidaire-|title=Mehdi Nemmouche sort du silence: \"Je suis solidaire\"|publisher=Rtl.be|accessdate=16 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140608100621/http://www.rtl.be/info/belgique/faitsdivers/1097831/mehdi-nemmouche-sort-du-silence-je-suis-solidaire-|archive-date=8 June 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> He has denied the charges against him.<ref>[https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21603489-jews-are-unnerved-europe-not-sinking-violent-anti-semitism-guns-and-ballot-boxes Of guns and ballot boxes: Jews are unnerved, but Europe is not sinking into violent anti-Semitism] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011021915/https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21603489-jews-are-unnerved-europe-not-sinking-violent-anti-semitism-guns-and-ballot-boxes |date=11 October 2017 }}, economist.com.</ref> On 29 July 2014, Nemmouche was [[Extradition|extradited]] to Belgium.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tijd.be/nieuws/politiek_economie_belgie/Verdachte_aanslag_Joods_Museum_uitgeleverd.9528324-3136.art|title=Verdachte aanslag Joods Museum uitgeleverd: De Tijd|publisher=Tijd.be|accessdate=29 July 2014|language=Dutch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140801060837/http://www.tijd.be/nieuws/politiek_economie_belgie/Verdachte_aanslag_Joods_Museum_uitgeleverd.9528324-3136.art|archive-date=1 August 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAnalysis of a telephone call made by [[Abdelhamid Abaaoud]] established that he was in contact with Nemmouche during January 2014. Abaaoud was the ringleader of [[November 2015 Paris attacks|a series of coordinated terrorist attacks]] in [[Paris]] that occurred on 13 November 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lemonde.fr/attaques-a-paris/article/2015/11/16/qui-est-abdelhamid-abaaoud-le-commanditaire-presume-des-attaques-de-paris_4811009_4809495.html |title=Abdelhamid Abaaoud, l\u2019instigateur pr\u00e9sum\u00e9 des attentats tu\u00e9 \u00e0 Saint-Denis |trans-title=Abdelhamid Abaaoud, the alleged instigator of the attacks killed at Saint-Denis |work=[[Le Monde]] |date=17 November 2015 |accessdate=20 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190508091731/https://www.lemonde.fr/attaques-a-paris/article/2015/11/16/qui-est-abdelhamid-abaaoud-le-commanditaire-presume-des-attaques-de-paris_4811009_4809495.html |archive-date=8 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Trial ===\nFollowing a two-month trial, Nemmouche was convicted for the shooting in March 2019 and sentenced to life in prison.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/mar/12/jewish-museum-killer-mehdi-nemmouche-sentenced-to-life-in-prison |title=Jewish museum killer sentenced to life in prison |author=Agence France-Presse |author-link=Agence France-Presse |date=12 March 2019 |access-date=25 June 2019 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian News & Media Limited]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190619014051/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/mar/12/jewish-museum-killer-mehdi-nemmouche-sentenced-to-life-in-prison |archive-date=19 June 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> His lawyers claimed he was framed and that the shooting was the work of foreign intelligence services. A second French national, Nacer Bendrer, was sentenced to 15 years in prison for supplying Nemmouche with the weapons used in the attack.<ref>{{cite web |title=Brussels Jewish Museum murders: Mehdi Nemmouche jailed for life |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-47533533 |website=bbc.com |publisher=BBC |accessdate=April 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401044547/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-47533533 |archive-date=1 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Court trial ==\nIn January 2019, the trial of Mehdi Nemmouche and Nacer Bendrer, who is suspected of being an [[accomplice]], started before the [[Court of assizes (Belgium)|assize court]] of Brussels. In the [[Judiciary of Belgium|Belgian criminal justice system]], an assize court is a non-permanent court that holds [[jury trial]]s on the most serious crimes. A few weeks before the actual start of the trial, a [[preliminary hearing]] took place on 20 December 2018, during which the list of [[witness]]es to be heard in the case was decided on. The [[defence attorney]]s of Nemmouche as well as Nemmouche himself opposed having his family members testify during the trial. According to Nemmouche's defence, this was because \"Mr Nemmouche did not want to argue on emotion, but on the facts\". His defence also requested to [[Adjournment|adjourn]] the case for two weeks, in order to give them the opportunity to study the case more in-depth. The adjournment of the case was rejected by the court, however. It was also decided that about 120 witnesses in total would be heard in the case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2018/12/20/enorme-veiligheidsmaatregelen-voor-voorbereidende-zitting-proces/|title=Geen uitstel voor proces Nemmouche over aanslag Joods museum, bijna 120 getuigen worden opgeroepen|last=Decr\u00e9|first=Hanne|last2=Verhaeghe|first2=Chris|date=20 December 2018|website=www.vrt.be|publisher=[[Vlaamse Radio- en Televisieomroeporganisatie|VRT NWS]]|language=Dutch|trans-title=No delay for trial Nemmouche about attack on Jewish museum, almost 120 witnesses will be summoned|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181221215344/https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2018/12/20/enorme-veiligheidsmaatregelen-voor-voorbereidende-zitting-proces/|archive-date=21 December 2018|url-status=|access-date=8 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 January 2019, three days before the start of the actual trial, the jurors on the assize jury were selected. For the [[jury selection]], 200 Belgian citizens were summoned to the [[Palais de Justice, Brussels|Palace of Justice of Brussels]], where the assize trial is held. A significant number of them asked to be exempt from [[jury duty]] for various reasons. After a dozen of juror candidates were [[Peremptory challenge|challenged]] by both the defence and the prosecution, eight men and four women were eventually empaneled as jurors. An additional twelve people, of which three men and nine women, were also selected as alternate jurors.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2019/01/07/ik-ben-rondgeleid-door-een-slachtoffer-ik-ben-half-doof-of/|title=\"Rondleiding door slachtoffer\", \"half doof\" of \"skivakantie\": excuses om niet in jury proces-Nemmouche te moeten zitten|last=Decr\u00e9|first=Hanne|date=7 January 2019|work=www.vrt.be|access-date=8 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107202800/https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2019/01/07/ik-ben-rondgeleid-door-een-slachtoffer-ik-ben-half-doof-of/|archive-date=7 January 2019|publisher=[[Vlaamse Radio- en Televisieomroeporganisatie|VRT NWS]]|language=Dutch|trans-title=\"Guided tour by victim\", \"half deaf\" or \"skiing holiday\": excuses not to have to serve on the jury in Nemmouche trial}}</ref>\n\nHenri Laquay, the lawyer of Nemmouche, argued that Nemmouche was innocent and that he had been set up by Israeli intelligence and Belgian police. According to Laquay, the Israeli couple that were killed in the shooting were not tourists, but members of [[Mossad]], the Israeli intelligence agency. Sebastien Courtoy, another of Nemmouche's lawyers, accused the police of manipulating evidence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20190115-frenchman-nemmouche-suspect-brussels-jewish-museum-attack-lawyers-set-mossad|title=Lawyers for Jewish museum attack suspect say their client was 'set up'|date=2019-01-16|website=France 24|language=en|access-date=2019-01-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190116232803/https://www.france24.com/en/20190115-frenchman-nemmouche-suspect-brussels-jewish-museum-attack-lawyers-set-mossad|archive-date=16 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Verdict ===\n{{multiple image\n | width = 150\n | direction = vertical\n | caption_align = center\n | image1=Verdict 2019-03-07.pdf\n | caption1=Jury verdict<br>(in French)\n | image2=Cour d'assises Bruxelles 12 mars 2019.pdf\n | caption2=Sentencing judgment<br>(in French)\n}}\nOn 7 March 2019, Mehdi Nemmouche was found guilty by the jury of the terrorist murders of the four individuals in the museum attack, and of the [[Criminal possession of a weapon|illegal possession of the weapons]] used in the attack. In the reasoning the jury gave for its [[verdict]], required by Belgian law, the main evidence against Nemmouche was summed up. The evidence against Nemmouche included the fact he was carrying the weapons used in the attack with him when he was arrested in Marseille, together with the clothing the perpetrator worn as seen on the security footage from the Museum. Both the weapons and the clothing had his [[DNA]] on them, and [[gunshot residue]] was also found on the clothing in question. A [[footprint]] of the sneakers he had with him was found in front of the entrance of the Museum. When he was arrested, he was also carrying some [[electronic media]] with him, on which videos were discovered wherein Nemmouche claimed responsibility for the attack in the name of [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIS]]. An [[Jihadist flag|ISIS flag]] used in the videos was found along the weapons Nemmouche had with him upon his arrest. The electronic media also contained data, such as [[web browsing history]], which proved Nemmouche had been planning the attack. A direct witness identified Nemmouche as being the perpetrator. Lastly, on a computer belonging to [[Najim Laachraoui]], one of the suicide bombers of the [[2016 Brussels bombings]], conversations were discovered wherein Nemmouche was described as a \"brother\", and plans were discussed to liberate him from his incarceration.<ref name=\"RawlinsonConvicted\">{{cite news|last1=Rawlinson|first1=Kevin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/mar/07/brussels-jewish-museum-terror-attack-french-citizen-convicted|title=Brussels Jewish museum terror attack: French citizen convicted|date=7 March 2019|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=15 April 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190311022456/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/mar/07/brussels-jewish-museum-terror-attack-french-citizen-convicted|archive-date=11 March 2019|website=}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Petitjean|first=Sophie|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/police-justice/article/2019/03/07/tuerie-du-musee-juif-nemmouche-reconnu-coupable-de-quatre-assassinats-terroristes_5432924_1653578.html|title=Proc\u00e8s du Mus\u00e9e juif de Bruxelles: Nemmouche reconnu coupable de quatre assassinats terroristes|date=7 March 2019|work=[[Le Monde]]|access-date=16 April 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401234616/https://www.lemonde.fr/police-justice/article/2019/03/07/tuerie-du-musee-juif-nemmouche-reconnu-coupable-de-quatre-assassinats-terroristes_5432924_1653578.html|archive-date=1 April 2020|language=French|trans-title=Trial over Jewish Museum of Brussels: Nemmouche found guilty of four terrorist murders}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Decr\u00e9|first=Hanne|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2019/03/07/nemmouche-schuldvraag/|title=Mehdi Nemmouche schuldig aan viervoudige terroristische moord in het Joods Museum, Bendrer is mededader|date=7 March 2019|work=[[Vlaamse Radio- en Televisieomroeporganisatie|VRT NWS]]|access-date=16 April 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191031012840/https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2019/03/07/nemmouche-schuldvraag/|archive-date=31 October 2019|language=Dutch|trans-title=Mehdi Nemmouche guilty of four counts of terrorist murder in Jewish Museum, Bendrer is co-author}}</ref>\n\nThe jury considered that the [[Real evidence|material evidence]] proved Nemmouche was the perpetrator of the attack. Based on the weapons used, the security footage of the Museum, and the [[Expert witness|expert testimony]] of the [[Medical examiner|medical examiners]] who examined the bodies of the victims, the jury found Nemmouche had the [[Intention (criminal law)|intention]] to kill. The jury furthermore affirmed the premeditated nature of the killings based on the preparatory acts Nemmouche carried out, such as the procurement of the weapons he used. The terrorist intentions of Nemmouche were upheld based on his [[Jihadism|jihadist]] stay in [[Syria]] in 2012, the videos he made in which he claimed responsibility for the attacks in the name of ISIS, and the conversations about Nemmouche retained from Najim Laachraoui's computer. The verdict also rejected the claim that Nemmouche was set up by intelligence officials. The jury lamented the lack of any element brought forward by the defence which would support those allegations. The existence of a setup was therefor deemed to lack \"sufficient plausibility and credibility\".<ref name=\"RawlinsonConvicted\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nAside from Nemmouche, the jury also found Nacer Bendrer guilty of being the co-author, and not just the [[accomplice]], of the terrorist attack by supplying the weapons Nemmouche used.<ref name=\"RawlinsonConvicted\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Sentence ===\nBoth men were sentenced on 12 March 2019: Nemmouche was sentenced to [[life imprisonment]], while Bendrer received a 15-year prison sentence. In addition, Nemmouche was sentenced to a 15-year period of judicial surveillance. This provision means that if he would ever be released on [[parole]], he would be monitored by a sentence enforcement court, which could potentially order his incarceration for an additional 15 years. Bendrer was also sentenced to a 5-year period of such judicial surveillance.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-47533533|title=Brussels Jewish Museum murders: Mehdi Nemmouche jailed for life|date=12 March 2019|work=[[BBC News]]|access-date=15 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Decr\u00e9|first=Hanne|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2019/03/11/nemmouche-en-bendrer-veroordeeld/|title=Mehdi Nemmouche krijgt levenslang voor aanslag op Joods Museum, mededader Nacer Bendrer 15 jaar|date=12 March 2019|work=[[Vlaamse Radio- en Televisieomroeporganisatie|VRT NWS]]|access-date=16 April 2020|url-status=live|last2=Verhaeghe|first2=Chris|language=Dutch|trans-title=Mehdi Nemmouche gets life sentence for attack on Jewish Museum, accomplice Nacer Bendrer 15 years}}</ref>\n\nIn its judgment, the court stated that the terrorist attack on the Jewish Museum constituted an attack on the fundamental values of Belgian society, in particular the [[Freedom of religion in Belgium|freedom of religion]] of the Jewish community of Belgium. The court considered Nemmouche's troubled upbringing to be no [[Mitigating factor|mitigating circumstance]] for such a grave act, and it also took into account the violent nature of the murders, Nemmouche's rejection of the [[Rechtsstaat|''rechtsstaat'']], and his complete lack of empathy and respect for his victims, amongst other factors. According to the court, he presented a high risk of [[recidivism]]. Regarding Bendrer on the other hand, the court described him as having played a decisive role in the attack by supplying the weapons used to Nemmouche. The court considered he knew what they would be used for, and was indifferent to the consequences to others. However, the court also upheld some mitigating circumstances, such as Bendrer having steered clear of any [[Islamic extremism]] since his arrest, and him having shown empathy and regret for the victims. Bendrer was deemed to present a low risk of recidivism.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Cassation and damages ===\n\nBendrer later lodged an appeal in cassation against his conviction with the [[Court of Cassation (Belgium)|Court of Cassation]]. This meant the civil part of the proceedings before the court of assizes (without the jury) with regards to [[damages]] had to be postponed. On 18 September 2019, the Court of Cassation rejected the appeal, which established the criminal sentence as final.<ref>{{cite news|last1=|first1=|url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/belgique-l-attentat-du-musee-juif-en-2014-definitivement-juge-20190918|title=Belgique: l'attentat du Mus\u00e9e juif en 2014 d\u00e9finitivement jug\u00e9|date=18 September 2019|work=|accessdate=15 April 2020|url-status=live|language=fr|trans-title=Belgium: final judgment over attack on Jewish Museum in 2014|website=[[Le Figaro]]}}</ref>\n\nSubsequently, on 22 October 2019 the court of assizes awarded 985,000 euro in damages to the victims' next of kin and the Jewish Museum, to be paid by both convicts.<ref name=\"\u201eBrusselsTimes\u201c\">{{cite news|last1=Galindo|first1=Gabriela|url=https://www.brusselstimes.com/all-news/belgium-all-news/74818/jewish-museum-terrorists-ordered-to-pay-nearly-e1-million-in-victim-compensation-mehdi-nemmouche-nacer-bendrer-terrorist-attacks/|title=Jewish Museum terrorists ordered to pay nearly \u20ac1 million in victim compensation|date=22 October 2019|work=[[The Brussels Times]]|accessdate=15 April 2020|url-status=live|website=}}</ref>\n\n== Reactions ==\n=== Domestic ===\n==== Government ====\nBelgium's Prime Minister [[Elio Di Rupo]] condemned the attack. \"In Belgium we are not accustomed to such acts of barbarity,\" he said.<ref name=\"MuseumAttack\"/> Belgian Foreign Minister [[Didier Reynders]], who arrived at the museum shortly after the shooting, wrote on [[Twitter]]: \"Shocked by the murders committed at the Jewish Museum, my thoughts go to the victims that I saw on the site and their families\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/dreynders/status/470210880215736320|title=Tweet by @dreynders|date=24 May 2014|work=[[Twitter]]|access-date=2 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220145047/https://twitter.com/dreynders/status/470210880215736320|archive-date=20 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Minister of the Interior, Jo\u00eblle Milquet speculated that anti-Semitism might be behind the shootings and Brussels Mayor [[Yvan Mayeur]] described them as a likely terrorist attack.<ref name=\"BrusselsAttack\">{{cite news|title=Four dead in shooting at Jewish museum in Brussels|url=http://www.jpost.com/Jewish-World/Jewish-News/Report-Three-dead-in-shooting-near-Jewish-museum-in-Brussels-353232|accessdate=26 May 2014|newspaper=Jerusalem Post|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140526074156/http://www.jpost.com/Jewish-World/Jewish-News/Report-Three-dead-in-shooting-near-Jewish-museum-in-Brussels-353232|archive-date=26 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Belgian politician [[Mischa\u00ebl Modrikamen]], leader of [[People's Party (Belgium)|a small conservative party]] and himself a member of Belgium's Jewish community, said \"Sadly, however, the actual attack comes as no surprise to us after years of living in an atmosphere of rampant anti-Semitism that often leads to violence.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jta.org/2014/05/25/news-opinion/world/museum-attack-comes-as-no-surprise-to-belgian-jews#ixzz32lSIg0wL|work=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]]|date=25 May 2014|author=Cnaan Lipshitz|title=Museum attack comes as no surprise to Belgian Jews|access-date=25 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016212930/http://www.jta.org/2014/05/25/news-opinion/world/museum-attack-comes-as-no-surprise-to-belgian-jews#ixzz32lSIg0wL|archive-date=16 October 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Organizations ====\nJoel Rubinfeld of the Belgian League Against Antisemitism described the act as \"the inevitable result of a climate that distills hatred... it will be necessary to use all legal means to silence the preachers of this hate who are responsible for spreading this virus of anti-Jewish hatred\", specifically mentioning the [[anti-Zionist]] and [[Holocaust denial|Holocaust-denying]] representative, [[Laurent Louis]], and controversial Black French comedian [[Dieudonn\u00e9 M'bala M'bala]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rtl.be/info/belgique/societe/1094180/fusillade-au-musee-juif-a-bruxelles-ce-qui-s-est-passe-etait-previsible-|title=Fusillade au Mus\u00e9e Juif \u00e0 Bruxelles: \"Ce qui s'est pass\u00e9 \u00e9tait pr\u00e9visible\"|trans-title=Shooting at the Jewish Museum in Brussels: \"What has happened was foreseeable\"|publisher=[[RTL Group]]|date=24 May 2014|access-date=25 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525213510/http://www.rtl.be/info/belgique/societe/1094180/fusillade-au-musee-juif-a-bruxelles-ce-qui-s-est-passe-etait-previsible-|archive-date=25 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rtbf.be/info/belgique/detail_la-nouvelle-ligue-belge-contre-l-antisemitisme-ne-concurrence-pas-le-mrax?id=8186077 |title=La nouvelle Ligue belge contre l'antis\u00e9mitisme \"ne concurrence pas le Mrax\" |publisher=Rtbf.be |date=27 January 2014 |language=fr |accessdate=25 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525233631/http://www.rtbf.be/info/belgique/detail_la-nouvelle-ligue-belge-contre-l-antisemitisme-ne-concurrence-pas-le-mrax?id=8186077 |archive-date=25 May 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.fr/2014/05/24/fusillade-musee-juif-bruxelles-morts-blesse_n_5385657.html |title=Une fusillade pr\u00e8s d'un mus\u00e9e juif \u00e0 Bruxelles fait trois morts et un bless\u00e9 grave |publisher=Huffingtonpost.fr |date=24 May 2014 |language=French |accessdate=25 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525200901/http://www.huffingtonpost.fr/2014/05/24/fusillade-musee-juif-bruxelles-morts-blesse_n_5385657.html |archive-date=25 May 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Louis denied Rubinfeld's accusations, suggesting that the attack could have been a [[false flag]] operation seeking to discredit him and his political party, ''[[Debout Les Belges!]]'' (Rise Up, Belgians), on the eve of the [[2014 Belgian federal election|Belgian federal election]]s.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tuerie au Mus\u00e9e juif de Bruxelles : Laurent Louis \" ne croit pas au hasard \"|trans-title=Killing at the Jewish Museum in Brussels: Laurent Louis \"doesn't believe in chance\"|language=fr|url=http://www.conspiracywatch.info/Tuerie-au-Musee-juif-de-Bruxelles-Laurent-Louis-ne-croit-pas-au-hasard_a1237.html|work=[[:fr:Conspiracy Watch|Conspiracy Watch]]|date=24 May 2014|access-date=25 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527232504/http://www.conspiracywatch.info/Tuerie-au-Musee-juif-de-Bruxelles-Laurent-Louis-ne-croit-pas-au-hasard_a1237.html|archive-date=27 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The League of Muslims in Belgium condemned the attack as \"barbaric\". In a statement the league said, \"These crimes with racist and anti-Semitic accents are unfortunately likely to reverse in our country the efforts of all those who, on a daily basis, are working for a society where everyone, regardless of his religious and philosophical beliefs, can live in dignity and respect.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Belgian Muslims condemn attack on Jewish Museum in Brussels|url=http://www.kuna.net.kw/ArticleDetails.aspx?id=2379185&language=en|accessdate=26 May 2014|newspaper=[[Kuwait News Agency]]|date=25 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527212328/http://www.kuna.net.kw/ArticleDetails.aspx?id=2379185&language=en|archive-date=27 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== International ===\n==== Countries====\nFrench President [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande]] condemned the \"horrifying killings with the greatest force.\" In a statement, he expressed France's solidarity with neighboring Belgium and condolences to the families of victims.<ref name=\"Jewish and world leaders slam Brussels shooting, urge greater security\">{{cite news |url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4523210,00.html |title=Jewish and world leaders slam Brussels shooting, urge greater security |work=Ynetnews |date=25 May 2014 |access-date=25 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525193503/http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4523210,00.html |archive-date=25 May 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Pope Francis]], who was visiting the [[Middle East]] at the time of the attacks, said he was deeply saddened by the killings in \"this criminal act of anti-Semitic hatred\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Investigators divided on terror motives in Brussels Jewish Museum shooting|url=http://www.jpost.com/Jewish-World/Jewish-News/Investigators-divided-on-terror-motives-of-Brussels-Jewish-museum-shooting-354441|date=27 May 2014|newspaper=Jerusalem Post|access-date=26 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527062400/http://www.jpost.com/Jewish-World/Jewish-News/Investigators-divided-on-terror-motives-of-Brussels-Jewish-museum-shooting-354441|archive-date=27 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> \"My thoughts go out to those who lost their lives in the attack in Brussels,\" he said. \"I entrust the victims to God.\"<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2014/05/26/uk-belgium-shooting-idUKKBN0E50IO20140526|title=Police hunt Brussels Jewish Museum gunman, France tightens security|author=Robert-Jan Bartunek|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=26 May 2014|access-date=27 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527215754/http://uk.reuters.com/article/2014/05/26/uk-belgium-shooting-idUKKBN0E50IO20140526|archive-date=27 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Israeli President [[Shimon Peres]] also called upon European leaders to act against \"any form of anti-Semitism\" which he said was \"rearing its head across the continent\".<ref name=\"timesofisrael\"/> Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] and Foreign Minister [[Avigdor Lieberman]] blamed [[Delegitimization of Israel#Rhetoric of delegitimization|anti-Israel incitement]], especially in Europe, for the shooting, stating, \"There are elements in Europe that rush to condemn the construction of a flat in Jerusalem but who do not rush to condemn, or offer only a weak condemnation of the murder of Jews here or in Europe itself.\"<ref name=\"timesofisrael\">{{cite news|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/after-belgium-attack-pm-pans-european-hypocrisy/#ixzz32kUNcDHp|title=After Belgium attack, PM pans European \u2018hypocrisy\u2019|newspaper=[[The Times of Israel]]|date=25 May 2014|accessdate=25 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525233001/http://www.timesofisrael.com/after-belgium-attack-pm-pans-european-hypocrisy/#ixzz32kUNcDHp|archive-date=25 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> He praised [[Elio Di Rupo]], who telephoned to express condolences and update the Israeli leader on the investigation.<ref name=\"timesofisrael\"/> Lieberman further stated that the attack was the result of European antisemitism and incitement against the Jewish State.<ref name=\"ynet-israel-reaction\">{{cite news |title=Netanyahu slams Brussels shooting as result of hateful incitement |url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4523230,00.html |last=Somfavli |first=Atilla |work=[[Ynetnews]] |date=25 May 2014 |accessdate=25 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525193505/http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4523230,00.html |archive-date=25 May 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nItalian President [[Giorgio Napolitano]] recalled \"the needing to keep in guard and be ready to wear out every regurgitation of antisemitism\" and declared \"I am always close to the world of Jewish communities yet again harshly hit\". [[Ministry of Interior (Italy)|Ministry of Interior]] [[Angelino Alfano]] declared \"Dead and injured from the Bruxelles' attack are also our dead and injured\" and stressed that \"there are no motives in the world that can allow all of this\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adnkronos.com/fatti/esteri/2014/05/24/belgio-sparatoria-vicino-museo-ebraico-bruxelles-tre-morti_OOFi52hDqZW34Bg04WBLKN.html |title=Bruxelles, spari al Museo ebraico: tre morti. Il ministro: \"Presunto attacco antisemita\" |publisher=Adnkronos |date=24 May 2014 |accessdate=29 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140703043850/http://www.adnkronos.com/fatti/esteri/2014/05/24/belgio-sparatoria-vicino-museo-ebraico-bruxelles-tre-morti_OOFi52hDqZW34Bg04WBLKN.html |archive-date=3 July 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Prime Minister of the Netherlands, [[Mark Rutte]], conveyed his condolences to the prime ministers of Belgium and Israel. The Dutch minister of Foreign affairs, [[Frans Timmermans]], expressed his solidarity to his Belgian colleague. He said that he was shocked by the cowardly attack.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nd.nl/artikelen/2014/mei/25/rutte-belt-met-di-rupo-over-aanval-brussel|title=Rutte belt met Di Rupo over aanval Brussel|trans-title=Rutte calls Di Rupio about Brussels attack|work=[[Nederlands Dagblad]]|agency=[[Novum]]|date=25 May 2014|accessdate=4 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140606222307/http://www.nd.nl/artikelen/2014/mei/25/rutte-belt-met-di-rupo-over-aanval-brussel|archive-date=6 June 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Carl Bildt]], [[Sweden|Swedish]] [[Minister for Foreign Affairs (Sweden)|Minister for Foreign Affairs]], wrote on [[Twitter]]: \"Despicable attack on the Jewish Museum in Brussels. An affront against the values our modern Europe represents.\"<ref>{{cite tweet |author= [[Carl Bildt]] |user= carlbildt|number= 470254110089150464 |date= 24 May 2014 |title= Despicable attack on the Jewish Museum in Brussels. An affront against the values our modern Europe represents. |access-date= 25 May 2014 }}</ref> [[Birgitta Ohlsson]], [[Minister for EU Affairs (Sweden)|Minister for EU Affairs]], also wrote on Twitter: \"I'm shocked about the anti-Semitic attack at the Jewish Museum in Brussels just one Day<!--[sic]--> before the elections to the European Parliament.\"<ref>{{cite tweet |author= [[Birgitta Ohlsson]] |user= birgittaohlsson|number= 470248298960683008 |date= 24 May 2014 |title= I'm shocked about the anti-Semitic attack at the Jewish Museum in Brussels just one Day before the elections to the European Parliament. |access-date= 25 May 2014 }}</ref> [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Turkey)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] issued a statement, offering condolences to the victims' families. In written statement, \"Turkey hopes the attack was not related to \"racist or [[anti-Semitic]]\" motives. Or else we will be very concerned over the result of the latest [[2014 European Parliament election|EU Parliament elections]], which was very disappointing.\" <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mfa.gov.tr/no_-175_-28-may-2014_-press-release-regarding-the-armed-attack-perpetrated-in-front-of-the-jewish-museum-in-brussels.en.mfa |title=No: 175, 28 May 2014, Press Release Regarding the Armed Attack Perpetrated in Front of the Jewish Museum in Brussels |publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Turkey)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Turkey]] |date=28 May 2014 |accessdate=5 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140606212148/http://www.mfa.gov.tr/no_-175_-28-may-2014_-press-release-regarding-the-armed-attack-perpetrated-in-front-of-the-jewish-museum-in-brussels.en.mfa |archive-date=6 June 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{verify quote|date=February 2019}}\n\n====Organizations====\n[[Roger Cukierman]], head of French Jewish Association ([[Conseil Repr\u00e9sentatif des Institutions juives de France|CRIF]]), called for more resources to be given to the French foreign intelligence service, the [[DGSE]], to track militants returning to France from Syria.<ref name=autogenerated2/> The European Jewish Association's General Director, Rabbi Menachem Margolin, thanked the European leaders who had condemned the attack for their remarks, but stressed that, \"condemnation after a predictable attack is nothing but a way to cleanse one\u2019s conscience...There is a need to establish a pan-European taskforce in order to annihilate anti-Semitism.\"<ref name=\"timesofisrael\"/> He later added that, \"Such an attack was to be expected in light of rising anti-Semitism in Europe. The governments of Europe have to take steps, words aren't enough.\"<ref name=\"Solidarity protests mark site of Brussels gun attack\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4523672,00.html|work=Ynetnews|title=Solidarity protests mark site of Brussels gun attack|date=26 May 2014|access-date=25 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140526014829/http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4523672,00.html|archive-date=26 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> A spokesman for [[United Nations]] Secretary General [[Ban Ki Moon]] said in a statement that the Secretary General \"reiterates his strong condemnation of all forms of racism, racial discrimination, xenophobia and related intolerance and trusts that Belgian authorities will do everything possible to bring the perpetrator or perpetrators of this crime to justice swiftly.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Ban Ki-Moon condemns Brussels shooting; Rome Jewish museum to open late|url=http://www.jta.org/2014/05/26/news-opinion/world/ban-ki-moon-condemns-brussels-shooting-rome-jewish-museum-to-open-late|date=26 May 2014|publisher=Jewish Telegraphic Agency|access-date=26 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140602023329/http://www.jta.org/2014/05/26/news-opinion/world/ban-ki-moon-condemns-brussels-shooting-rome-jewish-museum-to-open-late|archive-date=2 June 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> [[World Jewish Congress]] President [[Ronald Lauder|Ronald S. Lauder]] reacted with shock, saying \"Two years after Toulouse, and on the eve of the European elections, this despicable attack is yet another terrible reminder of the kind of threats Europe's Jews are currently facing.\"<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4523210,00.html|title=Jewish and world leaders slam Brussels shooting, urge greater security|publisher=ynet News|date=25 May 2014|access-date=25 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525193503/http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4523210,00.html|archive-date=25 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Antisemitism in contemporary Belgium]]\n*[[1981 Antwerp synagogue bombing]]\n*[[2011 Li\u00e8ge attack]]\n*[[2016 Brussels bombings]]\n\n{{Portal bar|Belgium}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Islamic terrorism in Europe}}\n{{Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant}}\n\n{{coord|50.8408|4.3534|display=title|format=dms|type:event_region:BE}}\n\n[[Category:2014 in Brussels]]\n[[Category:2014 in Judaism]]\n[[Category:2014 mass shootings in Europe]]\n[[Category:2014 murders in Europe]]\n[[Category:2010s murders in Belgium]]\n[[Category:2010s trials]]\n[[Category:21st-century attacks on synagogues and Jewish communal organizations]]\n[[Category:21st-century mass murder in Europe]]\n[[Category:Antisemitic attacks and incidents in Europe]]\n[[Category:Antisemitism in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Attacks on buildings and structures in 2014]]\n[[Category:Attacks on buildings and structures in Europe]]\n[[Category:Attacks on museums]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Filmed killings]]\n[[Category:Islam and antisemitism]]\n[[Category:Islamic terrorism in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Islamic terrorist incidents in 2014]]\n[[Category:Jewish Belgian history]]\n[[Category:Jews and Judaism in Brussels]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 2014]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in Europe]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Belgium]]\n[[Category:May 2014 crimes]]\n[[Category:May 2014 events in Europe]]\n[[Category:Murder trials]]\n[[Category:Terrorist incidents in Belgium in 2014]]\n[[Category:Terrorist incidents in Brussels]]\n[[Category:Trials in Belgium]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title            = {{nowrap|Jewish Museum of Belgium shooting}}\n| partof           = [[Terrorism in Belgium]] and [[Islamic terrorism in Europe (2014\u2013present)]]\n| image            = Bruxelles rue des Minimes 21.jpg\n| image_size       = 200px\n| alt              = \n| caption          = {{nowrap|The Jewish Museum of Belgium, pictured in 2009}}\n| map              = \n| map_size         = \n| map_alt          = \n| map_caption      = \n| location         = [[Jewish Museum of Belgium]]<br />[[Brussels]], [[Belgium]]\n| target           = \n| coordinates      = \n| date             = {{Start date|2014|05|24|df=y}}\n| time             = 15:50 [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| timezone         = [[UTC+02:00]]\n| type             = [[Mass shooting]]\n| fatalities       = 4\n| injuries         = \n| victims          = \n| perpetrators     = Mehdi Nemmouche<br>Nacer Bendrer (co-author)\n| susperp          = \n| weapons          = *[[Zastava M70]] rifle\n*[[.38 Special|.38-caliber]] revolver\n| numparts         = \n| dfens            = \n| motive           = [[Antisemitism]], [[terrorism|extremist beliefs]]\n}}\nOn 24 May 2014, a gunman opened fire at the [[Jewish Museum of Belgium]] in [[Brussels]], killing four people. Three died at the scene; a fourth was taken to the hospital and died on 6 June. On 30 May 2014, Mehdi Nemmouche, a 29-year-old [[France|French]] national of [[Algeria]]n origin, was arrested at [[Marseille]] in connection with the shooting. He is believed to have spent over a year in Syria and had links with radical Islamists.\n\n==Shooting==\nA man wearing a cap, carrying several bags and armed with a handgun and a [[Kalashnikov rifle]] arrived at the [[Jewish Museum of Belgium]], near the [[Sablon (Brussels)|Sablon]] in central Brussels, at around half past three.<ref name=gm>{{cite news|last=Casert|first=Raf|title=Belgium ramps up security for lone suspect in Jewish Museum attack|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/police-hunt-brussels-jewish-museum-shooter-france-tightens-security/article18835439/|archive-url=https://archive.is/20140527190719/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/police-hunt-brussels-jewish-museum-shooter-france-tightens-security/article18835439/|url-status=dead|archive-date=27 May 2014|accessdate=26 May 2014|newspaper=The Globe and the Mail|date=25 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lesoir.be/559864/article/actualite/belgique/2014-06-01/fusillade-au-musee-juif-bruxelles-un-francais-arrete|accessdate=6 June 2014|newspaper=[[Le Soir]]|date=1 June 2014|title=Fusillade au Mus\u00e9e juif de Bruxelles: un Fran\u00e7ais arr\u00eat\u00e9|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140604201419/http://www.lesoir.be/559864/article/actualite/belgique/2014-06-01/fusillade-au-musee-juif-bruxelles-un-francais-arrete|archive-date=4 June 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> He then opened fire, killing three people on site and critically wounding a fourth, who was soon taken to hospital<ref name=\"JP\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/Report-Israeli-couple-among-Brussels-Jewish-museum-shooting-victims-353251 |title=Report: Israeli couple among Brussels Jewish museum shooting victims |newspaper=The Jerusalem Post |date=25 May 2014 |accessdate=25 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525035315/http://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/Report-Israeli-couple-among-Brussels-Jewish-museum-shooting-victims-353251 |archive-date=25 May 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> and who died of his injuries on 6 June.<ref name=\"fourthvictim\">{{cite news|url=http://www.demorgen.be/dm/nl/30966/Schietpartij-aan-Joods-Museum-in-Brussel/article/detail/1910854/2014/06/06/Vierde-slachtoffer-aanslag-Joods-museum-overleden.dhtml|title=Vierde slachtoffer aanslag Joods museum overleden|date=6 June 2014|publisher=[[De Morgen]]|accessdate=6 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728223443/http://www.demorgen.be/dm/nl/30966/Schietpartij-aan-Joods-Museum-in-Brussel/article/detail/1910854/2014/06/06/Vierde-slachtoffer-aanslag-Joods-museum-overleden.dhtml|archive-date=28 July 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The attack lasted less than 90 seconds,<ref>{{cite news|title=Federaal parket gaat uit van terreuraanslag|url=http://www.hln.be/hln/nl/30962/Schietpartij-aan-Joods-Museum-in-Brussel/article/detail/1899346/2014/05/26/Federaal-parket-gaat-uit-van-terreuraanslag.dhtml|accessdate=27 May 2014|newspaper=[[Het Laatste Nieuws]]|date=26 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527020019/http://www.hln.be/hln/nl/30962/Schietpartij-aan-Joods-Museum-in-Brussel/article/detail/1899346/2014/05/26/Federaal-parket-gaat-uit-van-terreuraanslag.dhtml|archive-date=27 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> after which the shooter fled the scene on foot<ref name=gm /><ref name=\"Captured Jewish Museum shooting suspect carried weapons, gas mask\">{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/06/01/world/europe/france-belgium-jewish-shooting/ |title=Captured Jewish Museum shooting suspect carried weapons, gas mask |publisher=CNN |date=2 June 2014 |accessdate=29 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714233938/http://www.cnn.com/2014/06/01/world/europe/france-belgium-jewish-shooting |archive-date=14 July 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> and was partially captured by security cameras.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27567396|title=Belgian police in appeal to public over gunman identity|work=BBC News Online|accessdate=26 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525235650/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27567396|archive-date=25 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> According to police, he headed into a different part of downtown Brussels before disappearing.<ref name=\"Captured Jewish Museum shooting suspect carried weapons, gas mask\" /> According to security camera footage, the attacker appeared to wear a baseball-type cap covering-up his head, and a chest-mounted camera, like [[Mohammed Merah]], who filmed his acts during the 2012 [[Toulouse and Montauban shootings]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lalibre.be/actu/belgique/fusillade-a-bruxelles-le-parquet-qualifie-les-faits-de-terroristes-5382d19a35704f05d69d576a|work=[[La Libre Belgique|La Libre]]|date=26 May 2014|trans-title=Shooting in Brussels: prosecutors call the acts \"terrorism\"|language=fr|title=Fusillade \u00e0 Bruxelles: le parquet qualifie les faits de \"terroristes\"|access-date=27 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140528010605/http://www.lalibre.be/actu/belgique/fusillade-a-bruxelles-le-parquet-qualifie-les-faits-de-terroristes-5382d19a35704f05d69d576a|archive-date=28 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> although it was stated that the camera failed during filming.<ref name=\"Captured Jewish Museum shooting suspect carried weapons, gas mask\" /><ref name=\"Suspect in Jewish museum killings claimed responsibility in video\">{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2014/06/01/frenchman-suspected-ties-to-syria-jihadists-reportedly-arrested-in-connection/ |title=Suspect in Jewish museum killings claimed responsibility in video |publisher=Fox News |date=1 June 2014 |accessdate=29 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140705190438/http://www.foxnews.com/world/2014/06/01/frenchman-suspected-ties-to-syria-jihadists-reportedly-arrested-in-connection/ |archive-date=5 July 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe Belgian Minister of Foreign Affairs, [[Didier Reynders]], happened to be in the vicinity of the museum and heard the gunshots. The Minister of the Interior, [[Jo\u00eblle Milquet]], was also nearby and arrived on the scene a few minutes later.<ref name=\"MuseumAttack\"/>\n\n=== Victims ===\nFour people were killed in the shooting. Two of the victims were [[Israelis]], Emanuel and Miriam Riva, a middle-aged couple on holiday from [[Tel Aviv]], while a French woman named Dominique Sabrier was the third victim.\n\nA young Belgian man who worked at the museum, Alexandre Strens, was critically wounded<ref name=\"MuseumAttack\">{{cite news|title=Belgian police hunt gunman after Jewish museum murders|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/may/25/belgian-police-hunt-gunman-jewish-museum-murders-brussels|accessdate=25 May 2014|newspaper=The Guardian|agency=[[Agence France-Presse]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525221420/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/may/25/belgian-police-hunt-gunman-jewish-museum-murders-brussels|archive-date=25 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> and died of his wounds on 6 June. He was born in Morocco to a Jewish mother and [[Algeria]]n [[Berber people|Berber]] father, and his body was returned to [[Taza, Morocco]], for burial in a Muslim cemetery.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.english.rfi.fr/africa/20140610-fourth-victim-brussels-jewish-museum-killings-buried-muslim-cemetery-morocco |title=Fourth victim of Brussels Jewish Museum killings buried in Moroccan Muslim cemetery |publisher=[[Radio France Internationale]] |date=10 June 2014 |accessdate=16 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140615120222/http://www.english.rfi.fr/africa/20140610-fourth-victim-brussels-jewish-museum-killings-buried-muslim-cemetery-morocco |archive-date=15 June 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27733876|date=6 June 2014|title=Brussels Jewish Museum killings: Fourth victim dies|access-date=21 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180916160533/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27733876|archive-date=16 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://moroccantimes.com/2014/06/morocco-25-year-old-alexander-strens-buried-taza/ |title=Morocco: 25-Year-Old Alexander Strens to be buried in Taza |publisher=The Moroccan Times |date=9 June 2014 |accessdate=16 June 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140617034434/http://moroccantimes.com/2014/06/morocco-25-year-old-alexander-strens-buried-taza/ |archivedate=17 June 2014 }}</ref>\n\n== Investigation ==\nA nationwide manhunt was launched for the attacker, who was described as being of medium height and athletic build, and wearing a dark baseball cap. His image, partly obscured, was captured on [[Closed-circuit television|CCTV]]. A man who was seen driving from the museum was detained, but released after questioning, and remains a witness in the investigation.<ref name=\"ShootingSuspect\">{{cite news|title=Belgian police in appeal to public over gunman identity|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27567396|accessdate=19 June 2013|publisher=BBC|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525191330/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27567396|archive-date=25 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Deputy prosecutor Ine Van Wymersch said the shooter \"probably acted alone, was armed and well prepared.\" She stated that the motive for the attack was still \"open\".<ref name=\"news.nationalpost.com\">{{cite web |url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2014/05/25/photos-of-jewish-museum-shooter-released-as-belgium-launches-nationwide-manhunt-for-suspect-who-killed-four/ |title=Photos of Jewish Museum shooter released as Belgium launches manhunt for suspect who killed four &#124; National Post |publisher=News.nationalpost.com |date= |accessdate=29 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729081256/http://news.nationalpost.com/2014/05/25/photos-of-jewish-museum-shooter-released-as-belgium-launches-nationwide-manhunt-for-suspect-who-killed-four/ |archive-date=29 July 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> The attack was being investigated as a terrorist incident.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/europeennes-2014/article/2014/05/26/tueur-du-musee-la-belgique-choisit-une-juridiction-competente-en-matiere-de-terrorisme_4426217_4350146.html|date=26 May 2014|work=[[Le Monde]]|trans-title=Killings at the Belgian Jewish museum treated as \"terrorism\"|title=La tuerie du Mus\u00e9e juif de Bruxelles qualifi\u00e9e d'acte \" terroriste \"|access-date=29 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529223426/http://www.lemonde.fr/europeennes-2014/article/2014/05/26/tueur-du-musee-la-belgique-choisit-une-juridiction-competente-en-matiere-de-terrorisme_4426217_4350146.html|archive-date=29 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Perpetrator ===\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name = Mehdi Nemmouche\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = Mehdi Nemmouche\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1985|04|17|df=yes}} \n| birth_place = [[Roubaix]], [[France]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| nationality = [[France|French]], [[Algeria]]n\n| other_names = \n| criminal_charge = [[Robbery]] (2007) <br /> [[Murder]] (2014)\n| penalty = 5 years imprisonment (2007) <br /> Life in prison (2019)\n| conviction_status = Tried and found guilty\n| allegiance = \n| motive = [[Antisemitism]], [[Islamism]]\n| conviction = [[Robbery]] (2007), [[Murder]] (2019)\n| date =\n| time = \n| locations = \n| targets = \n| fatalities = \n| apprehended = 30 May 2014\n}}\n\n'''Mehdi Nemmouche''' ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u0647\u062f\u064a \u0646\u0645\u0648\u0634}}; born 17 April 1985), a 29-year-old French citizen, was arrested on 30 May 2014 at the [[Gare Saint-Charles (Marseille)|Saint-Charles]] railway station in [[Marseille]] in connection with the shooting. Nemmouche is suspected to have returned to France from [[Foreign rebel fighters in the Syrian Civil War|fighting for Islamist rebels]] in the [[Syrian Civil War]] in 2013.<ref name=\"BBC suspect\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27654505|title=Brussels Jewish Museum killings: Man held in Marseille|date=1 June 2014|work=BBC News|accessdate=1 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140601084139/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27654505|archive-date=1 June 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> He appears{{clarify|reason=Did he or didn't he + says who?|date=September 2017}} to have recorded a video bearing the flag of the rebel group [[Islamic State in Iraq and Syria]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/europe/article/2014/06/01/tuerie-de-bruxelles-un-suspect-francais-arrete_4429835_3214.html|title=Pourquoi Mehdi Nemmouche est le principal suspect de la tuerie de Bruxelles|date=1 June 2014|trans-title=Why Mehdi Nemmouche is the principal suspect of the killings in Brussels|language=fr|access-date=16 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140614151109/http://www.lemonde.fr/europe/article/2014/06/01/tuerie-de-bruxelles-un-suspect-francais-arrete_4429835_3214.html|archive-date=14 June 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nNemmouche was born in [[Roubaix]]. His father abandoned his mother before he was born and he was raised primarily by his grandmother and in group homes. Prior to leaving for Syria, he already had a long criminal history, including arrests for armed robbery, vehicle theft, and vandalism. He reportedly told hostages in Syria he was planning an attack in Paris on [[Bastille Day]].<ref name=lemonde>{{cite web|title=Mehdi Nemmouche: ce que l'on sait de son parcours|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/societe/article/2014/09/08/mehdi-nemmouche-ce-que-l-on-sait-de-son-parcours_4483458_3224.html|website=lemonde.fr|publisher=[[Le Monde]]|accessdate=10 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151121102022/http://www.lemonde.fr/societe/article/2014/09/08/mehdi-nemmouche-ce-que-l-on-sait-de-son-parcours_4483458_3224.html|archive-date=21 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nNemmouche had previously spent five years in prison where he is suspected to [[Islamist radicalization in European prisons|have been radicalized]].<ref name=BisserbeRadicalization>{{cite news|last1=Bisserbe|first1=Noemie|title=European Prisons Fueling Spread of Islamic Radicalism|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/european-prisons-fueling-spread-of-islamic-radicalism-1470001491|accessdate=23 August 2016|website=[[the Wall Street Journal]]|date=31 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160823000615/http://www.wsj.com/articles/european-prisons-fueling-spread-of-islamic-radicalism-1470001491|archive-date=23 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> He left for Syria only three weeks after being released from prison in September 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=Captured Jewish Museum shooting suspect carried weapons, gas mask|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/06/01/world/europe/france-belgium-jewish-shooting|date=2 June 2014|publisher=[[CNN]]|accessdate=2 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140604074132/http://edition.cnn.com/2014/06/01/world/europe/france-belgium-jewish-shooting|archive-date=4 June 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> If proven guilty, he will be the first European volunteer in the Syrian war who committed attacks upon returning to Europe.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mulholland|first=Rory|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/france/10868197/French-police-arrest-Syria-Jihadist-over-Brussels-Jewish-Museum-murders.html|title=French police arrest Syria jihadist over Brussels Jewish Museum murders|newspaper=Telegraph|date=1 June 2014|accessdate=29 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140721130618/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/france/10868197/French-police-arrest-Syria-jihadist-over-Brussels-Jewish-Museum-murders.html|archive-date=21 July 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> A number of items were recovered from a bag he was carrying while being detained, including a [[Kalashnikov rifle]], a [[.38 Special]] [[revolver]], nearly 330 rounds of ammunition for both weapons, gun parts, cameras, clothing, and a [[gas mask]]. A hidden file containing a 40-second video was discovered in one of the cameras; in it, Nemmouche's weapons are recorded and a voice, believed to belong to Nemmouche by police, claimed responsibility for the museum shooting in an audio commentary.<ref name=\"Captured Jewish Museum shooting suspect carried weapons, gas mask\"/><ref name=\"Suspect in Jewish museum killings claimed responsibility in video\"/> He was said to have had a white sheet emblazoned with the name of the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]].<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27660683|title=France arrests Syria jihad suspects as Nemmouche held|date=2 June 2014|work=BBC News|access-date=21 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180914035038/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27660683|archive-date=14 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nNemmouche, who has Algerian as well as French citizenship, resisted extradition to Belgium.<ref name=\"RTL\">{{cite web|author=Staff|url=http://www.rtl.be/info/belgique/faitsdivers/1097831/mehdi-nemmouche-sort-du-silence-je-suis-solidaire-|title=Mehdi Nemmouche sort du silence: \"Je suis solidaire\"|publisher=Rtl.be|accessdate=16 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140608100621/http://www.rtl.be/info/belgique/faitsdivers/1097831/mehdi-nemmouche-sort-du-silence-je-suis-solidaire-|archive-date=8 June 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> He has denied the charges against him.<ref>[https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21603489-jews-are-unnerved-europe-not-sinking-violent-anti-semitism-guns-and-ballot-boxes Of guns and ballot boxes: Jews are unnerved, but Europe is not sinking into violent anti-Semitism] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011021915/https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21603489-jews-are-unnerved-europe-not-sinking-violent-anti-semitism-guns-and-ballot-boxes |date=11 October 2017 }}, economist.com.</ref> On 29 July 2014, Nemmouche was [[Extradition|extradited]] to Belgium.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tijd.be/nieuws/politiek_economie_belgie/Verdachte_aanslag_Joods_Museum_uitgeleverd.9528324-3136.art|title=Verdachte aanslag Joods Museum uitgeleverd: De Tijd|publisher=Tijd.be|accessdate=29 July 2014|language=Dutch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140801060837/http://www.tijd.be/nieuws/politiek_economie_belgie/Verdachte_aanslag_Joods_Museum_uitgeleverd.9528324-3136.art|archive-date=1 August 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAnalysis of a telephone call made by [[Abdelhamid Abaaoud]] established that he was in contact with Nemmouche during January 2014. Abaaoud was the ringleader of [[November 2015 Paris attacks|a series of coordinated terrorist attacks]] in [[Paris]] that occurred on 13 November 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lemonde.fr/attaques-a-paris/article/2015/11/16/qui-est-abdelhamid-abaaoud-le-commanditaire-presume-des-attaques-de-paris_4811009_4809495.html |title=Abdelhamid Abaaoud, l\u2019instigateur pr\u00e9sum\u00e9 des attentats tu\u00e9 \u00e0 Saint-Denis |trans-title=Abdelhamid Abaaoud, the alleged instigator of the attacks killed at Saint-Denis |work=[[Le Monde]] |date=17 November 2015 |accessdate=20 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190508091731/https://www.lemonde.fr/attaques-a-paris/article/2015/11/16/qui-est-abdelhamid-abaaoud-le-commanditaire-presume-des-attaques-de-paris_4811009_4809495.html |archive-date=8 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Trial ===\nFollowing a two-month trial, Nemmouche was convicted for the shooting in March 2019 and sentenced to life in prison.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/mar/12/jewish-museum-killer-mehdi-nemmouche-sentenced-to-life-in-prison |title=Jewish museum killer sentenced to life in prison |author=Agence France-Presse |author-link=Agence France-Presse |date=12 March 2019 |access-date=25 June 2019 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian News & Media Limited]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190619014051/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/mar/12/jewish-museum-killer-mehdi-nemmouche-sentenced-to-life-in-prison |archive-date=19 June 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> His lawyers claimed he was framed and that the shooting was the work of foreign intelligence services. A second French national, Nacer Bendrer, was sentenced to 15 years in prison for supplying Nemmouche with the weapons used in the attack.<ref>{{cite web |title=Brussels Jewish Museum murders: Mehdi Nemmouche jailed for life |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-47533533 |website=bbc.com |publisher=BBC |accessdate=April 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401044547/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-47533533 |archive-date=1 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Court trial ==\nIn January 2019, the trial of Mehdi Nemmouche and Nacer Bendrer, who is suspected of being an [[accomplice]], started before the [[Court of assizes (Belgium)|assize court]] of Brussels. In the [[Judiciary of Belgium|Belgian criminal justice system]], an assize court is a non-permanent court that holds [[jury trial]]s on the most serious crimes. A few weeks before the actual start of the trial, a [[preliminary hearing]] took place on 20 December 2018, during which the list of [[witness]]es to be heard in the case was decided on. The [[defence attorney]]s of Nemmouche as well as Nemmouche himself opposed having his family members testify during the trial. According to Nemmouche's defence, this was because \"Mr Nemmouche did not want to argue on emotion, but on the facts\". His defence also requested to [[Adjournment|adjourn]] the case for two weeks, in order to give them the opportunity to study the case more in-depth. The adjournment of the case was rejected by the court, however. It was also decided that about 120 witnesses in total would be heard in the case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2018/12/20/enorme-veiligheidsmaatregelen-voor-voorbereidende-zitting-proces/|title=Geen uitstel voor proces Nemmouche over aanslag Joods museum, bijna 120 getuigen worden opgeroepen|last=Decr\u00e9|first=Hanne|last2=Verhaeghe|first2=Chris|date=20 December 2018|website=www.vrt.be|publisher=[[Vlaamse Radio- en Televisieomroeporganisatie|VRT NWS]]|language=Dutch|trans-title=No delay for trial Nemmouche about attack on Jewish museum, almost 120 witnesses will be summoned|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181221215344/https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2018/12/20/enorme-veiligheidsmaatregelen-voor-voorbereidende-zitting-proces/|archive-date=21 December 2018|url-status=|access-date=8 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 January 2019, three days before the start of the actual trial, the jurors on the assize jury were selected. For the [[jury selection]], 200 Belgian citizens were summoned to the [[Palais de Justice, Brussels|Palace of Justice of Brussels]], where the assize trial is held. A significant number of them asked to be exempt from [[jury duty]] for various reasons. After a dozen of juror candidates were [[Peremptory challenge|challenged]] by both the defence and the prosecution, eight men and four women were eventually empaneled as jurors. An additional twelve people, of which three men and nine women, were also selected as alternate jurors.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2019/01/07/ik-ben-rondgeleid-door-een-slachtoffer-ik-ben-half-doof-of/|title=\"Rondleiding door slachtoffer\", \"half doof\" of \"skivakantie\": excuses om niet in jury proces-Nemmouche te moeten zitten|last=Decr\u00e9|first=Hanne|date=7 January 2019|work=www.vrt.be|access-date=8 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107202800/https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2019/01/07/ik-ben-rondgeleid-door-een-slachtoffer-ik-ben-half-doof-of/|archive-date=7 January 2019|publisher=[[Vlaamse Radio- en Televisieomroeporganisatie|VRT NWS]]|language=Dutch|trans-title=\"Guided tour by victim\", \"half deaf\" or \"skiing holiday\": excuses not to have to serve on the jury in Nemmouche trial}}</ref>\n\nHenri Laquay, the lawyer of Nemmouche, argued that Nemmouche was innocent and that he had been set up by Israeli intelligence and Belgian police. According to Laquay, the Israeli couple that were killed in the shooting were not tourists, but members of [[Mossad]], the Israeli intelligence agency. Sebastien Courtoy, another of Nemmouche's lawyers, accused the police of manipulating evidence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20190115-frenchman-nemmouche-suspect-brussels-jewish-museum-attack-lawyers-set-mossad|title=Lawyers for Jewish museum attack suspect say their client was 'set up'|date=2019-01-16|website=France 24|language=en|access-date=2019-01-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190116232803/https://www.france24.com/en/20190115-frenchman-nemmouche-suspect-brussels-jewish-museum-attack-lawyers-set-mossad|archive-date=16 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Verdict ===\n{{multiple image\n | width = 150\n | direction = vertical\n | caption_align = center\n | image1=Verdict 2019-03-07.pdf\n | caption1=Jury verdict<br>(in French)\n | image2=Cour d'assises Bruxelles 12 mars 2019.pdf\n | caption2=Sentencing judgment<br>(in French)\n}}\nOn 7 March 2019, Mehdi Nemmouche was found guilty by the jury of the terrorist murders of the four individuals in the museum attack, and of the [[Criminal possession of a weapon|illegal possession of the weapons]] used in the attack. In the reasoning the jury gave for its [[verdict]], required by Belgian law, the main evidence against Nemmouche was summed up. The evidence against Nemmouche included the fact he was carrying the weapons used in the attack with him when he was arrested in Marseille, together with the clothing the perpetrator worn as seen on the security footage from the Museum. Both the weapons and the clothing had his [[DNA]] on them, and [[gunshot residue]] was also found on the clothing in question. A [[footprint]] of the sneakers he had with him was found in front of the entrance of the Museum. When he was arrested, he was also carrying some [[electronic media]] with him, on which videos were discovered wherein Nemmouche claimed responsibility for the attack in the name of [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIS]]. An [[Jihadist flag|ISIS flag]] used in the videos was found along the weapons Nemmouche had with him upon his arrest. The electronic media also contained data, such as [[web browsing history]], which proved Nemmouche had been planning the attack. A direct witness identified Nemmouche as being the perpetrator. Lastly, on a computer belonging to [[Najim Laachraoui]], one of the suicide bombers of the [[2016 Brussels bombings]], conversations were discovered wherein Nemmouche was described as a \"brother\", and plans were discussed to liberate him from his incarceration.<ref name=\"RawlinsonConvicted\">{{cite news|last1=Rawlinson|first1=Kevin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/mar/07/brussels-jewish-museum-terror-attack-french-citizen-convicted|title=Brussels Jewish museum terror attack: French citizen convicted|date=7 March 2019|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=15 April 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190311022456/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/mar/07/brussels-jewish-museum-terror-attack-french-citizen-convicted|archive-date=11 March 2019|website=}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Petitjean|first=Sophie|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/police-justice/article/2019/03/07/tuerie-du-musee-juif-nemmouche-reconnu-coupable-de-quatre-assassinats-terroristes_5432924_1653578.html|title=Proc\u00e8s du Mus\u00e9e juif de Bruxelles: Nemmouche reconnu coupable de quatre assassinats terroristes|date=7 March 2019|work=[[Le Monde]]|access-date=16 April 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401234616/https://www.lemonde.fr/police-justice/article/2019/03/07/tuerie-du-musee-juif-nemmouche-reconnu-coupable-de-quatre-assassinats-terroristes_5432924_1653578.html|archive-date=1 April 2020|language=French|trans-title=Trial over Jewish Museum of Brussels: Nemmouche found guilty of four terrorist murders}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Decr\u00e9|first=Hanne|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2019/03/07/nemmouche-schuldvraag/|title=Mehdi Nemmouche schuldig aan viervoudige terroristische moord in het Joods Museum, Bendrer is mededader|date=7 March 2019|work=[[Vlaamse Radio- en Televisieomroeporganisatie|VRT NWS]]|access-date=16 April 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191031012840/https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2019/03/07/nemmouche-schuldvraag/|archive-date=31 October 2019|language=Dutch|trans-title=Mehdi Nemmouche guilty of four counts of terrorist murder in Jewish Museum, Bendrer is co-author}}</ref>\n\nThe jury considered that the [[Real evidence|material evidence]] proved Nemmouche was the perpetrator of the attack. Based on the weapons used, the security footage of the Museum, and the [[Expert witness|expert testimony]] of the [[Medical examiner|medical examiners]] who examined the bodies of the victims, the jury found Nemmouche had the [[Intention (criminal law)|intention]] to kill. The jury furthermore affirmed the premeditated nature of the killings based on the preparatory acts Nemmouche carried out, such as the procurement of the weapons he used. The terrorist intentions of Nemmouche were upheld based on his [[Jihadism|jihadist]] stay in [[Syria]] in 2012, the videos he made in which he claimed responsibility for the attacks in the name of ISIS, and the conversations about Nemmouche retained from Najim Laachraoui's computer. The verdict also rejected the claim that Nemmouche was set up by intelligence officials. The jury lamented the lack of any element brought forward by the defence which would support those allegations. The existence of a setup was therefor deemed to lack \"sufficient plausibility and credibility\".<ref name=\"RawlinsonConvicted\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nAside from Nemmouche, the jury also found Nacer Bendrer guilty of being the co-author, and not just the [[accomplice]], of the terrorist attack by supplying the weapons Nemmouche used.<ref name=\"RawlinsonConvicted\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Sentence ===\nBoth men were sentenced on 12 March 2019: Nemmouche was sentenced to [[life imprisonment]], while Bendrer received a 15-year prison sentence. In addition, Nemmouche was sentenced to a 15-year period of judicial surveillance. This provision means that if he would ever be released on [[parole]], he would be monitored by a sentence enforcement court, which could potentially order his incarceration for an additional 15 years. Bendrer was also sentenced to a 5-year period of such judicial surveillance.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-47533533|title=Brussels Jewish Museum murders: Mehdi Nemmouche jailed for life|date=12 March 2019|work=[[BBC News]]|access-date=15 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Decr\u00e9|first=Hanne|url=https://www.vrt.be/vrtnws/nl/2019/03/11/nemmouche-en-bendrer-veroordeeld/|title=Mehdi Nemmouche krijgt levenslang voor aanslag op Joods Museum, mededader Nacer Bendrer 15 jaar|date=12 March 2019|work=[[Vlaamse Radio- en Televisieomroeporganisatie|VRT NWS]]|access-date=16 April 2020|url-status=live|last2=Verhaeghe|first2=Chris|language=Dutch|trans-title=Mehdi Nemmouche gets life sentence for attack on Jewish Museum, accomplice Nacer Bendrer 15 years}}</ref>\n\nIn its judgment, the court stated that the terrorist attack on the Jewish Museum constituted an attack on the fundamental values of Belgian society, in particular the [[Freedom of religion in Belgium|freedom of religion]] of the Jewish community of Belgium. The court considered Nemmouche's troubled upbringing to be no [[Mitigating factor|mitigating circumstance]] for such a grave act, and it also took into account the violent nature of the murders, Nemmouche's rejection of the [[Rechtsstaat|''rechtsstaat'']], and his complete lack of empathy and respect for his victims, amongst other factors. According to the court, he presented a high risk of [[recidivism]]. Regarding Bendrer on the other hand, the court described him as having played a decisive role in the attack by supplying the weapons used to Nemmouche. The court considered he knew what they would be used for, and was indifferent to the consequences to others. However, the court also upheld some mitigating circumstances, such as Bendrer having steered clear of any [[Islamic extremism]] since his arrest, and him having shown empathy and regret for the victims. Bendrer was deemed to present a low risk of recidivism.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Cassation and damages ===\n\nBendrer later lodged an appeal in cassation against his conviction with the [[Court of Cassation (Belgium)|Court of Cassation]]. This meant the civil part of the proceedings before the court of assizes (without the jury) with regards to [[damages]] had to be postponed. On 18 September 2019, the Court of Cassation rejected the appeal, which established the criminal sentence as final.<ref>{{cite news|last1=|first1=|url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/belgique-l-attentat-du-musee-juif-en-2014-definitivement-juge-20190918|title=Belgique: l'attentat du Mus\u00e9e juif en 2014 d\u00e9finitivement jug\u00e9|date=18 September 2019|work=|accessdate=15 April 2020|url-status=live|language=fr|trans-title=Belgium: final judgment over attack on Jewish Museum in 2014|website=[[Le Figaro]]}}</ref>\n\nSubsequently, on 22 October 2019 the court of assizes awarded 985,000 euro in damages to the victims' next of kin and the Jewish Museum, to be paid by both convicts.<ref name=\"\u201eBrusselsTimes\u201c\">{{cite news|last1=Galindo|first1=Gabriela|url=https://www.brusselstimes.com/all-news/belgium-all-news/74818/jewish-museum-terrorists-ordered-to-pay-nearly-e1-million-in-victim-compensation-mehdi-nemmouche-nacer-bendrer-terrorist-attacks/|title=Jewish Museum terrorists ordered to pay nearly \u20ac1 million in victim compensation|date=22 October 2019|work=[[The Brussels Times]]|accessdate=15 April 2020|url-status=live|website=}}</ref>\n\n== Reactions ==\n=== Domestic ===\n==== Government ====\nBelgium's Prime Minister [[Elio Di Rupo]] condemned the attack. \"In Belgium we are not accustomed to such acts of barbarity,\" he said.<ref name=\"MuseumAttack\"/> Belgian Foreign Minister [[Didier Reynders]], who arrived at the museum shortly after the shooting, wrote on [[Twitter]]: \"Shocked by the murders committed at the Jewish Museum, my thoughts go to the victims that I saw on the site and their families\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/dreynders/status/470210880215736320|title=Tweet by @dreynders|date=24 May 2014|work=[[Twitter]]|access-date=2 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220145047/https://twitter.com/dreynders/status/470210880215736320|archive-date=20 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Minister of the Interior, Jo\u00eblle Milquet speculated that anti-Semitism might be behind the shootings and Brussels Mayor [[Yvan Mayeur]] described them as a likely terrorist attack.<ref name=\"BrusselsAttack\">{{cite news|title=Four dead in shooting at Jewish museum in Brussels|url=http://www.jpost.com/Jewish-World/Jewish-News/Report-Three-dead-in-shooting-near-Jewish-museum-in-Brussels-353232|accessdate=26 May 2014|newspaper=Jerusalem Post|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140526074156/http://www.jpost.com/Jewish-World/Jewish-News/Report-Three-dead-in-shooting-near-Jewish-museum-in-Brussels-353232|archive-date=26 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Belgian politician [[Mischa\u00ebl Modrikamen]], leader of [[People's Party (Belgium)|a small conservative party]] and himself a member of Belgium's Jewish community, said \"Sadly, however, the actual attack comes as no surprise to us after years of living in an atmosphere of rampant anti-Semitism that often leads to violence.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jta.org/2014/05/25/news-opinion/world/museum-attack-comes-as-no-surprise-to-belgian-jews#ixzz32lSIg0wL|work=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]]|date=25 May 2014|author=Cnaan Lipshitz|title=Museum attack comes as no surprise to Belgian Jews|access-date=25 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016212930/http://www.jta.org/2014/05/25/news-opinion/world/museum-attack-comes-as-no-surprise-to-belgian-jews#ixzz32lSIg0wL|archive-date=16 October 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Organizations ====\nJoel Rubinfeld of the Belgian League Against Antisemitism described the act as \"the inevitable result of a climate that distills hatred... it will be necessary to use all legal means to silence the preachers of this hate who are responsible for spreading this virus of anti-Jewish hatred\", specifically mentioning the [[anti-Zionist]] and [[Holocaust denial|Holocaust-denying]] representative, [[Laurent Louis]], and controversial Black French comedian [[Dieudonn\u00e9 M'bala M'bala]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rtl.be/info/belgique/societe/1094180/fusillade-au-musee-juif-a-bruxelles-ce-qui-s-est-passe-etait-previsible-|title=Fusillade au Mus\u00e9e Juif \u00e0 Bruxelles: \"Ce qui s'est pass\u00e9 \u00e9tait pr\u00e9visible\"|trans-title=Shooting at the Jewish Museum in Brussels: \"What has happened was foreseeable\"|publisher=[[RTL Group]]|date=24 May 2014|access-date=25 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525213510/http://www.rtl.be/info/belgique/societe/1094180/fusillade-au-musee-juif-a-bruxelles-ce-qui-s-est-passe-etait-previsible-|archive-date=25 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rtbf.be/info/belgique/detail_la-nouvelle-ligue-belge-contre-l-antisemitisme-ne-concurrence-pas-le-mrax?id=8186077 |title=La nouvelle Ligue belge contre l'antis\u00e9mitisme \"ne concurrence pas le Mrax\" |publisher=Rtbf.be |date=27 January 2014 |language=fr |accessdate=25 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525233631/http://www.rtbf.be/info/belgique/detail_la-nouvelle-ligue-belge-contre-l-antisemitisme-ne-concurrence-pas-le-mrax?id=8186077 |archive-date=25 May 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.fr/2014/05/24/fusillade-musee-juif-bruxelles-morts-blesse_n_5385657.html |title=Une fusillade pr\u00e8s d'un mus\u00e9e juif \u00e0 Bruxelles fait trois morts et un bless\u00e9 grave |publisher=Huffingtonpost.fr |date=24 May 2014 |language=French |accessdate=25 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525200901/http://www.huffingtonpost.fr/2014/05/24/fusillade-musee-juif-bruxelles-morts-blesse_n_5385657.html |archive-date=25 May 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Louis denied Rubinfeld's accusations, suggesting that the attack could have been a [[false flag]] operation seeking to discredit him and his political party, ''[[Debout Les Belges!]]'' (Rise Up, Belgians), on the eve of the [[2014 Belgian federal election|Belgian federal election]]s.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tuerie au Mus\u00e9e juif de Bruxelles : Laurent Louis \" ne croit pas au hasard \"|trans-title=Killing at the Jewish Museum in Brussels: Laurent Louis \"doesn't believe in chance\"|language=fr|url=http://www.conspiracywatch.info/Tuerie-au-Musee-juif-de-Bruxelles-Laurent-Louis-ne-croit-pas-au-hasard_a1237.html|work=[[:fr:Conspiracy Watch|Conspiracy Watch]]|date=24 May 2014|access-date=25 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527232504/http://www.conspiracywatch.info/Tuerie-au-Musee-juif-de-Bruxelles-Laurent-Louis-ne-croit-pas-au-hasard_a1237.html|archive-date=27 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The League of Muslims in Belgium condemned the attack as \"barbaric\". In a statement the league said, \"These crimes with racist and anti-Semitic accents are unfortunately likely to reverse in our country the efforts of all those who, on a daily basis, are working for a society where everyone, regardless of his religious and philosophical beliefs, can live in dignity and respect.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Belgian Muslims condemn attack on Jewish Museum in Brussels|url=http://www.kuna.net.kw/ArticleDetails.aspx?id=2379185&language=en|accessdate=26 May 2014|newspaper=[[Kuwait News Agency]]|date=25 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527212328/http://www.kuna.net.kw/ArticleDetails.aspx?id=2379185&language=en|archive-date=27 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== International ===\n==== Countries====\nFrench President [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande]] condemned the \"horrifying killings with the greatest force.\" In a statement, he expressed France's solidarity with neighboring Belgium and condolences to the families of victims.<ref name=\"Jewish and world leaders slam Brussels shooting, urge greater security\">{{cite news |url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4523210,00.html |title=Jewish and world leaders slam Brussels shooting, urge greater security |work=Ynetnews |date=25 May 2014 |access-date=25 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525193503/http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4523210,00.html |archive-date=25 May 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Pope Francis]], who was visiting the [[Middle East]] at the time of the attacks, said he was deeply saddened by the killings in \"this criminal act of anti-Semitic hatred\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Investigators divided on terror motives in Brussels Jewish Museum shooting|url=http://www.jpost.com/Jewish-World/Jewish-News/Investigators-divided-on-terror-motives-of-Brussels-Jewish-museum-shooting-354441|date=27 May 2014|newspaper=Jerusalem Post|access-date=26 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527062400/http://www.jpost.com/Jewish-World/Jewish-News/Investigators-divided-on-terror-motives-of-Brussels-Jewish-museum-shooting-354441|archive-date=27 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> \"My thoughts go out to those who lost their lives in the attack in Brussels,\" he said. \"I entrust the victims to God.\"<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2014/05/26/uk-belgium-shooting-idUKKBN0E50IO20140526|title=Police hunt Brussels Jewish Museum gunman, France tightens security|author=Robert-Jan Bartunek|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=26 May 2014|access-date=27 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527215754/http://uk.reuters.com/article/2014/05/26/uk-belgium-shooting-idUKKBN0E50IO20140526|archive-date=27 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Israeli President [[Shimon Peres]] also called upon European leaders to act against \"any form of anti-Semitism\" which he said was \"rearing its head across the continent\".<ref name=\"timesofisrael\"/> Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] and Foreign Minister [[Avigdor Lieberman]] blamed [[Delegitimization of Israel#Rhetoric of delegitimization|anti-Israel incitement]], especially in Europe, for the shooting, stating, \"There are elements in Europe that rush to condemn the construction of a flat in Jerusalem but who do not rush to condemn, or offer only a weak condemnation of the murder of Jews here or in Europe itself.\"<ref name=\"timesofisrael\">{{cite news|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/after-belgium-attack-pm-pans-european-hypocrisy/#ixzz32kUNcDHp|title=After Belgium attack, PM pans European \u2018hypocrisy\u2019|newspaper=[[The Times of Israel]]|date=25 May 2014|accessdate=25 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525233001/http://www.timesofisrael.com/after-belgium-attack-pm-pans-european-hypocrisy/#ixzz32kUNcDHp|archive-date=25 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> He praised [[Elio Di Rupo]], who telephoned to express condolences and update the Israeli leader on the investigation.<ref name=\"timesofisrael\"/> Lieberman further stated that the attack was the result of European antisemitism and incitement against the Jewish State.<ref name=\"ynet-israel-reaction\">{{cite news |title=Netanyahu slams Brussels shooting as result of hateful incitement |url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4523230,00.html |last=Somfavli |first=Atilla |work=[[Ynetnews]] |date=25 May 2014 |accessdate=25 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525193505/http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4523230,00.html |archive-date=25 May 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nItalian President [[Giorgio Napolitano]] recalled \"the needing to keep in guard and be ready to wear out every regurgitation of antisemitism\" and declared \"I am always close to the world of Jewish communities yet again harshly hit\". [[Ministry of Interior (Italy)|Ministry of Interior]] [[Angelino Alfano]] declared \"Dead and injured from the Bruxelles' attack are also our dead and injured\" and stressed that \"there are no motives in the world that can allow all of this\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adnkronos.com/fatti/esteri/2014/05/24/belgio-sparatoria-vicino-museo-ebraico-bruxelles-tre-morti_OOFi52hDqZW34Bg04WBLKN.html |title=Bruxelles, spari al Museo ebraico: tre morti. Il ministro: \"Presunto attacco antisemita\" |publisher=Adnkronos |date=24 May 2014 |accessdate=29 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140703043850/http://www.adnkronos.com/fatti/esteri/2014/05/24/belgio-sparatoria-vicino-museo-ebraico-bruxelles-tre-morti_OOFi52hDqZW34Bg04WBLKN.html |archive-date=3 July 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Prime Minister of the Netherlands, [[Mark Rutte]], conveyed his condolences to the prime ministers of Belgium and Israel. The Dutch minister of Foreign affairs, [[Frans Timmermans]], expressed his solidarity to his Belgian colleague. He said that he was shocked by the cowardly attack.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nd.nl/artikelen/2014/mei/25/rutte-belt-met-di-rupo-over-aanval-brussel|title=Rutte belt met Di Rupo over aanval Brussel|trans-title=Rutte calls Di Rupio about Brussels attack|work=[[Nederlands Dagblad]]|agency=[[Novum]]|date=25 May 2014|accessdate=4 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140606222307/http://www.nd.nl/artikelen/2014/mei/25/rutte-belt-met-di-rupo-over-aanval-brussel|archive-date=6 June 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Carl Bildt]], [[Sweden|Swedish]] [[Minister for Foreign Affairs (Sweden)|Minister for Foreign Affairs]], wrote on [[Twitter]]: \"Despicable attack on the Jewish Museum in Brussels. An affront against the values our modern Europe represents.\"<ref>{{cite tweet |author= [[Carl Bildt]] |user= carlbildt|number= 470254110089150464 |date= 24 May 2014 |title= Despicable attack on the Jewish Museum in Brussels. An affront against the values our modern Europe represents. |access-date= 25 May 2014 }}</ref> [[Birgitta Ohlsson]], [[Minister for EU Affairs (Sweden)|Minister for EU Affairs]], also wrote on Twitter: \"I'm shocked about the anti-Semitic attack at the Jewish Museum in Brussels just one Day<!--[sic]--> before the elections to the European Parliament.\"<ref>{{cite tweet |author= [[Birgitta Ohlsson]] |user= birgittaohlsson|number= 470248298960683008 |date= 24 May 2014 |title= I'm shocked about the anti-Semitic attack at the Jewish Museum in Brussels just one Day before the elections to the European Parliament. |access-date= 25 May 2014 }}</ref> [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Turkey)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] issued a statement, offering condolences to the victims' families. In written statement, \"Turkey hopes the attack was not related to \"racist or [[anti-Semitic]]\" motives. Or else we will be very concerned over the result of the latest [[2014 European Parliament election|EU Parliament elections]], which was very disappointing.\" <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mfa.gov.tr/no_-175_-28-may-2014_-press-release-regarding-the-armed-attack-perpetrated-in-front-of-the-jewish-museum-in-brussels.en.mfa |title=No: 175, 28 May 2014, Press Release Regarding the Armed Attack Perpetrated in Front of the Jewish Museum in Brussels |publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Turkey)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Turkey]] |date=28 May 2014 |accessdate=5 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140606212148/http://www.mfa.gov.tr/no_-175_-28-may-2014_-press-release-regarding-the-armed-attack-perpetrated-in-front-of-the-jewish-museum-in-brussels.en.mfa |archive-date=6 June 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{verify quote|date=February 2019}}\n\n====Organizations====\n[[Roger Cukierman]], head of French Jewish Association ([[Conseil Repr\u00e9sentatif des Institutions juives de France|CRIF]]), called for more resources to be given to the French foreign intelligence service, the [[DGSE]], to track militants returning to France from Syria.<ref name=autogenerated2/> The European Jewish Association's General Director, Rabbi Menachem Margolin, thanked the European leaders who had condemned the attack for their remarks, but stressed that, \"condemnation after a predictable attack is nothing but a way to cleanse one\u2019s conscience...There is a need to establish a pan-European taskforce in order to annihilate anti-Semitism.\"<ref name=\"timesofisrael\"/> He later added that, \"Such an attack was to be expected in light of rising anti-Semitism in Europe. The governments of Europe have to take steps, words aren't enough.\"<ref name=\"Solidarity protests mark site of Brussels gun attack\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4523672,00.html|work=Ynetnews|title=Solidarity protests mark site of Brussels gun attack|date=26 May 2014|access-date=25 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140526014829/http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4523672,00.html|archive-date=26 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> A spokesman for [[United Nations]] Secretary General [[Ban Ki Moon]] said in a statement that the Secretary General \"reiterates his strong condemnation of all forms of racism, racial discrimination, xenophobia and related intolerance and trusts that Belgian authorities will do everything possible to bring the perpetrator or perpetrators of this crime to justice swiftly.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Ban Ki-Moon condemns Brussels shooting; Rome Jewish museum to open late|url=http://www.jta.org/2014/05/26/news-opinion/world/ban-ki-moon-condemns-brussels-shooting-rome-jewish-museum-to-open-late|date=26 May 2014|publisher=Jewish Telegraphic Agency|access-date=26 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140602023329/http://www.jta.org/2014/05/26/news-opinion/world/ban-ki-moon-condemns-brussels-shooting-rome-jewish-museum-to-open-late|archive-date=2 June 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> [[World Jewish Congress]] President [[Ronald Lauder|Ronald S. Lauder]] reacted with shock, saying \"Two years after Toulouse, and on the eve of the European elections, this despicable attack is yet another terrible reminder of the kind of threats Europe's Jews are currently facing.\"<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4523210,00.html|title=Jewish and world leaders slam Brussels shooting, urge greater security|publisher=ynet News|date=25 May 2014|access-date=25 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525193503/http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4523210,00.html|archive-date=25 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Antisemitism in contemporary Belgium]]\n*[[1981 Antwerp synagogue bombing]]\n*[[2011 Li\u00e8ge attack]]\n*[[2016 Brussels bombings]]\n\n{{Portal bar|Belgium}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Islamic terrorism in Europe}}\n{{Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant}}\n\n{{coord|50.8408|4.3534|display=title|format=dms|type:event_region:BE}}\n\n[[Category:2014 in Brussels]]\n[[Category:2014 in Judaism]]\n[[Category:2014 mass shootings in Europe]]\n[[Category:2014 murders in Europe]]\n[[Category:2010s murders in Belgium]]\n[[Category:2010s trials]]\n[[Category:21st-century attacks on synagogues and Jewish communal organizations]]\n[[Category:21st-century mass murder in Europe]]\n[[Category:Antisemitic attacks and incidents in Europe]]\n[[Category:Antisemitism in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Attacks on buildings and structures in 2014]]\n[[Category:Attacks on buildings and structures in Europe]]\n[[Category:Attacks on museums]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Filmed killings]]\n[[Category:Islam and antisemitism]]\n[[Category:Islamic terrorism in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Islamic terrorist incidents in 2014]]\n[[Category:Jewish Belgian history]]\n[[Category:Jews and Judaism in Brussels]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 2014]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in Europe]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Belgium]]\n[[Category:May 2014 crimes]]\n[[Category:May 2014 events in Europe]]\n[[Category:Murder trials]]\n[[Category:Terrorist incidents in Belgium in 2014]]\n[[Category:Terrorist incidents in Brussels]]\n[[Category:Trials in Belgium]]\n", "name_user": "Brentjee", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jewish_Museum_of_Belgium_shooting"}
{"title_page": "Roman Catholic Diocese of Iesi", "text_new": "{{Infobox diocese\n| jurisdiction      = Diocese<!-- Type of jurisdiction: i.e. Diocese or Archdiocese -->\n| name              = Iesi\n| latin             = Dioecesis Aesina\n| local             = <!-- Name in the native language -->\n| image             = Jesi-SanSettimio.jpg\n| image_size        = 255px\n| image_alt         = \n| caption           = Cathedral in [[Iesi]]\n<!---- Locations ---->\n| country           = Italy\n| metropolitan      =  \n| territory         = \n| province          = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Ancona-Osimo|Ancona-Osimo]]\n| coordinates       = <!-- Use {{coord}} -->\n<!---- Statistics ---->\n| area_km2          = 315\n| population        = 80,930 (est.)\n| population_as_of  = 2016\n| catholics         = 75,300 (guess)<!-- Number of Catholics in the diocese -->\n| catholics_percent = 93.0\n| parishes          = 41<!-- Number of parishes in the diocese -->\n| churches          = <!-- Number of churches in the diocese -->\n| congregations     = <!-- Number of congregations in the diocese -->\n| schools           = <!-- Number of church supported schools in the diocese -->\n| members           = <!-- Number of members in the diocese -->\n<!---- Information ---->\n| denomination      = [[Catholic Church]]\n| rite              = [[Roman Rite]]\n| established       = 6th Century\n| cathedral         = Basilica Cattedrale di S. Settimio\n| cocathedral       = \n| patron            = \n| priests           = 35 (diocesan)<br />23 (Religious Orders)<br />11 Permanent Deacons<!-- Number of priests in the diocese -->\n<!---- Current leadership ---->\n| pope              = {{Incumbent pope}} <!-- DO NOT CHANGE. This will update the Popes Automatically as they change -->\n| bishop_title      = Bishop\n| bishop            = [[Gerardo Rocconi]]\n| coadjutor         = \n| auxiliary_bishops = \n| vicar_general     = \n| emeritus_bishops  = \n<!---- Map ---->\n| map               = Roman Catholic Diocese of Jesi in Italy.jpg\n| map_alt           = Locator map of diocese of Jesi\n| map_caption       = \n<!---- Website ---->\n| website           = [http://www.jesi.chiesacattolica.it/index.html Diocesi di Jesi] {{in lang|it}}\n| footnotes         = \n}}\nThe  '''diocese of [[Iesi]]''' ({{lang-la|Dioecesis Aesina}}) is a Catholic ecclesiastical territory in the [[Marche]], Italy. It is a [[suffragan]] of the [[archdiocese of Ancona-Osimo]].<ref name=CathHierIesi>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/djesi.html \"Diocese of Iesi\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]'' David M. Cheney. Retrieved February 29, 2016. {{Self-published source|date=March 2019}}</ref><ref name=GCathIesi>[http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/jesi0.htm \"Diocese of Jesi\"] ''GCatholic.org.'' Gabriel Chow. Retrieved February 29, 2016. {{Self-published source|date=March 2019}}</ref> The diocese itself prefers the spelling Jesi.\n\n==History==\n[[Saint Septimius]], supposedly martyred in 307, has been venerated as the first bishop of [[Jesi]] since the 15th century.<ref>There is no reference to him whatever until 1469. Joannes Periero, S.J., \"De S. Septimio episc. et mart.\", in: ''Acta Sanctorum Septembris'' Tomus VI (Antwerp: Bernard vander Plassche 1757), pp. 408-410.</ref> [[Saint Florianus]], who was cast into the [[Esino]] in the [[Diocletian persecution]], is also venerated (perhaps he is confounded with Saint Florianus who was cast into the Enus or Anisus). Other bishops of antiquity were Calumniosus (c. 647) and Honestus. Their relics were discovered in 1623.\n\nThe future emperor [[Frederick II, Holy Roman Emperor|Frederick II]] was born in Jesi on 26 December 1194. His mother, [[Constance, Queen of Sicily]], was on her way to join her husband, [[Henry VI, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry VI]], who had been crowned King of Sicily at Palermo on the previous day. At Jesi she was overcome by sudden labor pains, and, anticipating the birth of an heir, the people erected a pavilion for her in the town square, so that the birth might take place amid a large complement of witnesses.<ref>{{cite book|author1=J.L.A. Huillard-Breholles|author2=H. de Albertis de Luynes|title=Historia diplomatica Friderici Secundi. Pr\u00e9face et introduction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BQxYAAAAcAAJ&pg=PP5|year=1859|publisher=Plon|location=Paris|language=French|page=clxxvii}}</ref> Fifteen cardinals and bishops witnessed the birth of the baby Frederick.<ref>Albert of S. Maria in State, ''Annales Stadenses'', in: ''Monumenta Germaniae Historica'', Scriptores XVI (Hannover: Hahn 1859), p. 352.</ref>\n\nOn 30 May 1247, [[Pope Innocent IV]] rejected the election of one of the Canons of the Cathedral Chapter, [[Armannus]], as bishop of Jesi, on the grounds that the Canons were excommunicated due to their support of the Emperor Frederick II. One Canon, however, named Montanario, was loyal to the Holy See and had escaped to Ancona from Jesi; he notified the Pope that he elected the Franciscan Gualterio. Innocent ordered the Rector of the March of Ancona, Marcellino Aretino, and Bishop Philip of Fermo to investigate the election and consult with Canon Montanario, and provide the new bishop.<ref>{{cite book|editor=Rodenberg, Carolus|title=Epistolae saeculi XIII e regestis pontificum Romanorum selectae|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VH0_AQAAMAAJ&pg=RA5-PA71|series=Monumenta Germaniae Historica|volume=Tomus II|year=1887|publisher=Apud Weidmannos|location=Berlin|language=German, Latin|pages=275, no. 373}} Baldassini, p. 57, and ''Appendix'' pp. xviii-xix.</ref> The Franciscan Gualtiero, an Englishman, was appointed. He was a friend of [[John of Parma]], general of the order and patron of the [[Franciscan Spirituals]].<ref>Gualterius is spoken of by Salimbene as \"bonus cantor, bonus praedicator, bonus dictator.\" Fra Salimbene of Parma, ''Chronica Fr. Salimbene Parmensis Ordinis Minorum'' (Parmae : Ex officina Petri Fiaccadorii, 1857), pp. 317-319 (under the year 1284). By ''dictator'', Salimbene means that Gualterius was a good writer.</ref>\n\nBishop Severinus in 1237 laid the foundations of the new cathedral;<ref>Ughelli, I, p. 282.</ref> the old cathedral, dedicated to Saint Nicholas of Myra, was outside the city, and in the eighteenth century had fallen into ruin.<ref>Baldassini, p. 159.</ref> In its current form, the cathedral is the result of restorations and renovations carried out by Bishop Antonio Fonseca.<ref>Baldaassini, p. 382.</ref>\n\nThe cathedral was and is administered by a Chapter, composed of a Prior and ten Canons.<ref>Cappelletti, p. 313. Ritzler-Sefrin, V, p. 71 note 1; VI, p. 68 note 1. Diocesi di Jesi, [http://www.jesi.chiesacattolica.it/diocesi.html        ''Guida diocesana 2018''] (Press the gray bar entitled \"Scarica la Guida Diocesana\"), page 9; retrieved: 5 March 2019.</ref> Up until the middle of the 15th century the Canons were required to live in the ''Canonica'', unless individually dispensed. Pope Paul II (1464\u20131471) dispensed the Canons from this obligation.<ref>Baldassini, p. 342.</ref> The best-known of the Canons was Marcello Cervini, who became [[Pope Marcellus II]] (1555).<ref>Baldassini, p. 343.</ref>\n\n[[Gabriele del Monte]] (1554) introduced the reforms of the [[Council of Trent]], which he had attended. His successors were Cardinal [[Pope Paul V|Camillo Borghese]] (1597), afterwards Pope Paul V; Cardinals [[Tiberio Cenci]] (1621) and [[Alderano Cybo]] (1656), noted for their benefactions; Bishop Antonio Fonseca (1724), who founded a hospital. [[Cardinal Caprara]], afterwards [[Archbishop of Milan]], who concluded the Concordat with Napoleon, was Bishop of Jesi (1800\u201302). He was succeeded by [[Antonio Odescalchi]], who was deported to Milan by the French in 1809, dying in exile in Cesano Boscone in 1812.<ref>Umberto Benigni (1910), [http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/08372a.htm \"Jesi.\"] ''The Catholic Encyclopedia'' Vol. 8. (New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1910); retrieved: 28 February 2019. {{cite book|editor=Simonetta Bernardi|title=La religione e il trono: Pio VIII nell'Europa del suo tempo : Convegno di studi : Cingoli, 12-13 giugno 1993|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JTfkAAAAMAAJ|year=1995|publisher=La Fenice edizioni|location=Roma|language=Italian|isbn=978-88-86171-14-4|page=7}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 August 1972, by the Bull ''Qui apostolico officio'', [[Pope Paul VI]] created the new ecclesiastical province of Ancona, and granted its archbishop the status of Metropolitan. The ecclesiastical province was assigned the suffragan dioceses of Jesi (Aesina) and Osimo (Auximana).<ref>''Acta Apostolicae Sedis'' [https://www.vatican.va/archive/aas/documents/AAS-64-1972-ocr.pdf An. et Vol. LXIV] (Citt\u00e0 del Vaticano: Typis Polyglottis Vaticanis 1972), pp. 664-665.</ref>\n\n===Synods===\n\nA diocesan synod was an irregularly held, but important, meeting of the bishop of a diocese and his clergy. Its purpose was (1) to proclaim generally the various decrees already issued by the bishop; (2) to discuss and ratify measures on which the bishop chose to consult with his clergy; (3) to publish statutes and decrees of the diocesan synod, of the provincial synod, and of the Holy See.<ref name=\"XIV1842\">{{cite book|author=Benedictus XIV|title=Benedicti XIV ... De Synodo dioecesana libri tredecim|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tj0F8czA8XsC&pg=PA51|volume=Tomus primus|year=1842|publisher=Hanicq|location=Mechlin|language=Latin|pages=42\u201349|chapter=Lib. I. caput secundum. De Synodi Dioecesanae utilitate}} John Paul II, Constitutio Apostolica ''de Synodis Dioecesanis Agendis'' (March 19, 1997): [https://www.vatican.va/archive/aas/documents/AAS-89-1997-ocr.pdf ''Acta Apostolicae Sedis'' 89] (1997), pp. 706-727.</ref>\n\nBishop Marco Agrippa Dandini (1599\u20131603) held a diocesan synod in Jesi on 16 September 1600.<ref>Marco Agrippa Dandini, ''Decreta in Diocesana Synodo Aesina promulgata a perillustr. et Reverendissimo d. d. Marco Agrippa Dandino, Nob. Caesenate Dei et Apostolicae Sedis gratia Episcopo Aesino. Die 16 Septembris 1600'' (Jesi: Petrus de Farris 1600).</ref> Bishop Tiberio Cenci (1621\u20131653) held a synod on 10 May 1626,<ref>''Decreta Synodi dioec. celebratae sub Illustriss. et reverendiss. d. d. Tyberio Cincio, Episc. Aesin., die decima mensis Maij MDCXXVI'' (Jesi: Gregorius Arnazzini 1626).</ref> and, as Cardinal, another synod on 23 September 1649.<ref>''Constitutiones sancitae in synodo dioecesana ab Eminentiss. et Reverendiss. D. D. Tiberio, tit. S. Callisti S. R. E. Presbytero Cardinali, Cincio, Episcopo Aesino, die XXIII septembris M.DC.XXXXIX'' (Fermo: Andrea de Montibus 1649).</ref> Cardinal Alderano Cybo (1656\u20131671) held a diocesan synod in Jesi from 4 to 6 July 1658.<ref>{{cite book|author=Alderano Cybo|title=Ordinationes, et decreta in Synodo \u00c6sina IV. V. et VI Iulii M.DC.LVIII. celebrata, etc|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gld93kmqYVkC&pg=PA223|year=1665|publisher=Apud Franciscum Seraphinum|location=Ancona|language=Latin}}</ref> Cardinal Pietro Matteo Petrucci held his first diocesan synod on 26\u201428 April 1683. He held his second diocesan synod in Jesi on 21 March 1695.<ref name=\"Jesi1695\">{{cite book|author=Pietro Matteo Petrucci|title=Secunda dioecesana aesina Synodus ab eminentiss. ac reuerendiss. d. d. Petro Matthaeo S.R.E. card. Petruccio ... In sua cathedrali ecclesia celebrata anno 1695|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S37Sa5GNyzcC&pg=PP1|year=1695|publisher=typis Heredum Pannelli, & Angeli Antonij Monticelli|location=Macerata|language=Latin}} J.-D. Mansi (ed.), ''Sacrorum Conciliorum nova et amplissima collectio'', editio novissima, Tomus XXXVI<sup>ter</sup> (Arnhem & Leipzig: H. Welter 1924), pp. 469, 495, 659.</ref>\n\nOn 23 April 1708, Bishop Alessandro Fedele (1696\u20131715) held a diocesan synod, whose decisions were published in 1713.<ref>''Synodus dioecesana ab illustriss. ac Reverendiss. d. Alexandro Fideli, Dei et Apostolicae Sedis Episcopo... in ecclesia cathedrali sub die 23 Aprilis celebrata, anno a reparata salute 1708'' (Jesi: Alexandrelli et Benedicti 1713).</ref> Bishop Antonio Fonseca held a diocesan synod in the Cathedral on 25 to 27 May 1727. The synodal decrees were published.<ref>{{cite book|author=Antonio Fonseca|title=Constitutiones synodales Aesinae ... habitae diebus 25. 26. et 27 mensis Maji 1727|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OARNAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA1|year=1728|publisher=Joh. Bapt. de Julius|location=Jesi|language=Latin}}</ref> He held a second diocesan synod on 26 and 27 September 1741, and its constitutions too were published.<ref>{{cite book|author=Antonio Fonseca|title=Secunda dioecesana Synodus Aesina celebrata diebus 26 et 27 Septembris 1741|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sA5NAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA1|year=1741|publisher=Joannes Bapt. de Julius|location=Jesi|language=Latin}}</ref> From 14 June to 16 June 1772, Bishop Ubaldo Baldassini, B. (1764\u20131786) held a diocesan synod, and published its synodal constitutions.<ref>''Sanctae Aesinae Ecclesiae Synodales Constitutiones ab illustrissimo et reverendissimo domino Domino Ubaldo Baldassino, Dei et Apostolicae Sedis gratia Episcopo Aesino... in dioecesanis comitiis editae diebus XIV, XV, XVI Junii, anno reparatae slautis MDCCLXXII'' (Jesi: Pietro Paolo Bonelli 1772).</ref>\n\nCardinal Carlo Luigi Morichini (1854\u20131871) presided over a diocesan synod on 15\u201417 November 1857.<ref>''Synodus dioecesana ab Eminentissimo et Reverendissimo Domino Carolo Aloysio Tituli S. Onuphrii S. R. E. Presbytero Cardinali Morichini Archipeiscopo Episcopo Aesino, celebrata in Ecclesia Cathedrali diebus xv, xvi, xvii novembris MDCCCLVII.'' (Aesii: Vincentius Cherubini 1857).</ref>\n\nBishop Oscar Serfilippi (1978\u20132006) held a diocesan synod in Jesi on 24 January 1982.<ref>''Find a Grave'', [https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/27651687/oscar-serfilippi \"Rev. Oscar Serfilippi\"]; retrieved: 9 March 2019.</ref>\n\n==Bishops of Iesi==\n===to 1100===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n:'''...''' \n: ? Septimius<ref>There is no reference to Septimius before 1469. Lanzoni, pp. 491-492: ''Prima del 1469 nessuna carta, nessuna memoria, nessun monumento di Iesi parla di un s. Settimio venerato nella cattedrale o in altro luogo; e la stessa cattedrale non era denominata da lui, ma dal SS. Salvatore''....</ref>\n:'''...''' \n:[Martianus (501)]<ref>Martianus is listed as a bishop of Jesi by Gams, p. 700, but Lanzoni, p. 492, points out that he was actually Bishop of Aeca (Aecanus, not Aesinus).</ref>\n:'''...''' \n*Calompiosus (c. 647)<ref>He is also called Calcompios and Calumniosus. Gams, p. 700.</ref>\n*Honestus (attested 680)<ref>Gams, p. 700. J.-D. Mansi (ed.), ''Sacrorum Conciliorum nova et amplissima collectio'', editio novissima, Tomus XI (Florence: A. Zatta 1773), p. 773.</ref>\n*Petrus (attested 743)<ref>Bishop Petrus was present at the first Roman synod of [[Pope Zacharias]]. Ughelli, I, p. 282. J.-D. Mansi (ed.), ''Sacrorum Conciliorum nova et amplissima collectio'', editio novissima, Tomus XII (Florence: A. Zatta 1776), p. 384c: ''Petrus Esis'', ''Petro Esino''.</ref>\n:'''...''' \n*Anastasius (attested 853)<ref>Bishop Anastasius did not attend the Roman synod of [[Pope Leo IV]] of 853, but he sent his deacon, Aimo, to represent him. J.-D. Mansi (ed.), ''Sacrorum Conciliorum nova et amplissima collectio'', editio novissima, Tomus XIV (Venice: A. Zatta 1769), p. 1020. Cappelletti, VII, p. 277.</ref>\n:'''...''' \n*Eberhard (attested 967)<ref>Bishop Eberhard was present at the Synod of Ravenna on 25 April 967. Gerhard Schwartz (1907), [https://archive.org/details/MN42020ucmf_1 ''Die Besetzung der Bist\u00fcmer Reichsitaliens unter den s\u00e4chsischen und salischen Kaisern: mit den Listen der Bisch\u00f6fe, 951-1122'']. Leipzig: B.G. Teubner. p.&nbsp;247. (in German)</ref>\n:'''...''' \n:[Martianus (attested 1027)]<ref>Martianus was Bishop of Cesena, not Jesi. Schwartz, p. 247, note 1. Detlev Jasper, [http://daten.digitale-sammlungen.de/~db/0009/bsb00096352/images/index.html?id=00096352&nativeno=93 ''Die Konzilien Deutschlands und Reichsitaliens 1023 - 1059''] [[MGH Concilia VIII]] (Hannover: Hahn 2010), p. 93.</ref>\n:'''...''' \n{{Div col end}}\n\n===from 1100 to 1500===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*Raynaldus (1164\u20131175)<ref>Gams, p. 700.</ref>\n*Grimoaldus\n*Crescentius (attested 1207)<ref>Baldassini, p. 367. Gams, p. 700. Eubel, ''Hierarchia catholica'' I, p. 75</ref>\n*Philippus<ref>Philippus: Cappelletti, VII, p. 279.</ref>\n*Severinus (attested 1230, 1235, 1237)<ref>Severinus is named in an inscription of 1237 on a marble plaque above the main door of the cathedral. Ughelli, p. 282. Cappelletti, VII, p. 279.</ref>\n:Armannus (Hermannus)<ref>Armannus was never more than an intrusive bishop-elect. He was elected by the Cathedral Chapter, but the Chapter had been excommunicated and had no right to participate in an election. His election was quashed by Pope Innocent IV on 30 May 1247. {{cite book|editor=Rodenberg, Carolus|title=Epistolae saeculi XIII e regestis pontificum Romanorum selectae|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VH0_AQAAMAAJ&pg=RA5-PA71|series=Monumenta Germaniae Historica|volume=Tomus II|year=1887|publisher=Apud Weidmannos|location=Berlin|language=German, Latin|pages=275, no. 373}}</ref>\n*Gualterus, O.Min.\n*Crescentius (1252\u20131263)<ref>Eubel, I, p. 75.</ref>\n*Bonajuncta, O.Min. (1263\u20131267)\n*Hugo (1267\u2013 )\n*Ioannes (1289\u20131295)<ref>Ioannes: Gams, p. 700 column 2. Eubel, I, p. 75.</ref>\n*Leonardus (1295\u20131311)<ref>Leonardo: Gams, p. 700 column 2. Eubel, I, p. 75.</ref>\n*Francesco Alfani (1312\u20131342)<ref>Francesco: Gams, p. 700 column 2. Eubel, I, p. 75.</ref>\n*Francesco Jordani Brancaleoni (1342\u20131350)<ref>Francesco was a native of Spoleto. He was appointed Bishop of Jesi by [[Pope Clement VI]] on 18 July 1342. Gams, p. 700 column 2. Eubel, I, p. 75.</ref>\n*Nicolaus de Pisis, O.E.S.A. (1350\u2013c. 1370)<ref>Bishop Nicolaus was still in office in 1361. Cappelletti, p. 288. Eubel, I, p. 75, states that he served until his death, but does not give a date.</ref>\n*Giovanni Zeminiani Rizardi, O.P. (1371\u20131373)\n*Berardus de Beysiaco, O.E.S.A. (1373\u20131391?)<ref>Ughelli, I, p. 283, calls him Bernardus, and states that he died in 1391.</ref>\n*? Pietro Borghese (? attested c. 1380)<ref>Pietro is said to have belonged to the famous Sienese family. He may have been intruded during the Western Schism. Knowledge of him comes only from an entry in Prospero Mendosio, citing an entry in Ugurgerio's ''De ponpis Senensibus'', who quotes from a genealogical work on the family by Celsus Cittadinus. Ughelli, pp. 282-283. Baldassini, p. 370.</ref>\n*Tommaso Pierleone (1391\u20131400)<ref>Pierleone had been elected bishop of Ascoli Piceno in 1390, and was still bishop-elect when transferred to Jesi on 12 July 1391 by [[Pope Boniface IX]]. He resigned the bishopric in 1400, in order to enter the monastery of [[San Lorenzo fuori le mura]] in Rome. Baldassari, pp. 370-371. Ughelli, p. 283. Eubel, I, pp. 75, 111.</ref>\n*Ludovico (Aloysius) Francisci Alfani (1400\u20131405)<ref>Luigi Alfani was appointed on 2 June 1400 by [[Pope Boniface IX]] of the Roman Obedience in the Western Schism. He had been abbot of the monastery of S. Paolo on the Arno in the diocese of Pisa. Baldassini, p. 371. Eubel, I, p. 75.</ref>\n*Jacobus Bonriposi (1405\u20131418)<ref>Bonriposi was appointed on 7 October 1405 by [[Pope Innocent VII]] of the Roman Obedience in the Western Schism. He was transferred to the diocese of Narni by [[Pope Martin V]] on 31 January 1418. He died in 1455. Baldassini, p. 371. Eubel, I, p. 75, 357.</ref>\n*Blondus Conchi (1418\u2013 )\n*Lazarus ( ? \u20131425)\n*[[Innocenzo de Comite]] (30 May 1425 \u2013 1443)<ref>Eubel, I, p. 75.</ref>\n:'''...''' \n*[[Thomas Ghisleri]] (5 Oct 1463 \u20131505)<ref>Ghislieri died on 6 June 1505. Baldassini, p. 372. Eubel, ''Hierarchia catholica'' II, p. 81 with note 1.</ref>\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===from 1500 to 1800===\n*Angelo Ripanti (1505\u20131513)<ref>Ripanti: Eubel, ''Hierarchia catholica'' III, p. 97.</ref>\n*Pietro Paolo Venanzio (1513\u20131519)<ref>Venanzio was appointed on 2 September 1513. He served until 1519. Eubel, III, p. 97.</ref>\n*Antonio de Spello (1519\u20131540)<ref>Spello: Eubel, III, p. 97.</ref>\n*[[Benedetto Conversini]] (1540\u20131553)<ref>A native of Pistoia, Conversini was Rector of the University of Pisa in 1518. He was Vice-Legate in Viterbo, and served as Bishop of Bertinoro (Veneto) from 1537 to 1540. On 21 March 1538 he was named Governor of the city of Rome and Vice-Chamberlain, a position he held for five years. He was transferred to the diocese of Jesi by [[Pope Paul III]] on 10 June 1540. During this time he was also Governor of Bologna, and President of the Romagna. He died at Castel del Piano (Jesi) in June 1553. {{cite book|author=Enrico Binde|title=Notizia biografica di Monsignor Benedetto Conversini, Pistoiese, Vescovo d'Iesi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C5NeAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA19|year=1851|publisher=Ranieri Guasti|location=Prato|language=Italian|page=19}} {{cite book|author=Vittorio Capponi|title=Biografia pistoiese|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kIbqYIeoNgMC&pg=PA136|year=1883|publisher=Tipografia Rossetti|location=Pistoia|language=Italian|pages=136\u2013138}} Eubel, III, pp. 97, 139 with note 5.</ref>\n*[[Gabriele Del Monte]] (10 Nov 1554 \u2013 27 Apr 1597 Died)<ref>Del Monte was the grand-nephew of [[Pope Julius III]], and the nephew of Cardinal Cristoforo Ciocchi del Monte. He participated in the [[Council of Trent]], and in accordance with its decrees, he founded the diocesan seminary. Cappelletti, VII, pp. 300-301. {{cite book|author=Ciro Zenobi|title=L' Episcopato Jesino di Monsignore Gabriele del Monte: (1554-1597)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EYjNNAEACAAJ|year=1979|publisher=Pontifical Lateran University|location=Rome|language=Italian}}</ref>\n*[[Pope Paul V|Camillo Borghese]] (1597\u20131599)<ref>Borghese was appointed Bishop of Jesi in the papal Consistory of 14 April 1597. He resigned the See on 2 August 1599. Gauchat, ''Hierarchia catholica'' IV, p. 71.</ref>\n*[[Marco Agrippa Dandini]] (1599\u20131603 Died)<ref>A native of Cesena, Dandini was appointed Bishop of Jesi by [[Pope Clement VIII]] on 2 August 1599. He died in Cesena on 20 October 1603 at the age of forty-six. Ughelli, I, p. 285. Gauchat, p. 71.</ref>\n*[[Pirro Imperoli]] (1604\u20131617)<ref>Imperioli had been Auditor and Vicar General of Cardinal Borghese when he was Bishop of Jesi. He was the first Canon Penitentiary of the Cathedral Chapter. He was named Bishop of Jesi by [[Pope Clement VIII]] on 28 January 1604. {{cite book|title=Studia Picena|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LNJ4Pw9dsbwC|year=1939|publisher=Pontificio Seminario marchigiano Pio 11.|location=Fano|language=Italian|page=143}} Cappelletti, VII, p. 302. Gauchat, p. 71 with note 4.</ref>\n*[[Marcello Pignatelli]], [[Theatines|C.R.]] (13 Nov 1617 \u2013 1621 Died)<ref>Cappelletti, VII, p. 302. Gauchat, p. 71 with note 5.</ref>\n*[[Tiberio Cenci]] (1621\u20131653)<ref>Cenci was a Roman, the nephew of Cardinal Marcello Lante. He held the degree ''[[Doctor of both laws|Doctor in utroque iure]]'', and was a Referendary of the Tribunal of the Two Signatures. In 1612 he was Governor of Jesi. He was named Bishop of Jesi in the papal consistory of 24 November 1621; there is no record of his consecration. On 20 April 1622 Cenci was named Governor of Loreto by [[Pope Gregory XV]]. In 1623 he discovered the purported remains of Saint Septimius. He was appointed a cardinal on 6 March 1645. He died on 26 February 1653, at the age of 73, according to his funeral inscription in the cathedral of Jesi. Cappelletti, p. 303. Gauchat, p. 71 with note 6.</ref>\n*Cardinal [[Giacomo Corradi]] (21 Apr 1653 \u2013 Apr 1656 Resigned)<ref>A native of Ferrara, Corradi had been  He was named a cardinal by [[Pope Innocent X]] on 19 February 1652, and was appointed to the [[titular church]] of S. Maria trans Tiberim. He  was appointed bishop of Jesi in the consistory of 21 April 1653, and was consecrated a bishop by Cardinal Fabio Chigi on 1 May 1553. On 10 April 1655, he was appointed pro-Datary of His Holiness, which required his residence in Rome; he held the post until his death. He died in Rome on 17 January 1666. Baldassini, pp. 377-378. Gauchat, pp. 30 no. 27, with notes 1 and 2; 71 with note 7.</ref>\n*[[Alderano Cibo]] (24 Apr 1656 \u2013 10 Dec 1671 Resigned)\n*[[Lorenzo Cibo]] (Cybo) (18 Jan 1671 \u2013 17 Aug 1680 Died)<ref>Cibo: Ritzler-Sefrin, ''Hierarchia catholica'' V, p. 71 with note 3.</ref>\n*[[Pier Matteo Petrucci]], [[Oratory of Saint Philip Neri|C.O.]] (14 Apr 1681 \u20131695/1696)<ref>Petrucci was still bishop when he held his second diocesan synod in Jesi on 21 March 1695. {{cite book|author=Pietro Matteo Petrucci|title=Secunda dioecesana aesina Synodus ab eminentiss. ac reuerendiss. d. d. Petro Matthaeo S.R.E. card. Petruccio ... In sua cathedrali ecclesia celebrata anno 1695|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S37Sa5GNyzcC&pg=PP1|year=1695|publisher=typis Heredum Pannelli, & Angeli Antonij Monticelli|location=Macerata|language=Latin}} J.-D. Mansi (ed.), ''Sacrorum Conciliorum nova et amplissima collectio'', editio novissima, Tomus XXXVI<sup>ter</sup> (Arnhem & Leipzig: H. Welter 1924), pp. 469, 495, 659. Ritzler-Sefrin, V, p. 71 with note 4.</ref>\n*[[Alessandro Fedele]] (20 Feb 1696 \u2013 7 Apr 1715 Died)<ref>Fedele: Ritzler-Sefrin, V, p. 71 with note 5.</ref>\n*Francesco Antonio Giattini (7 Dec 1716 \u2013 27 Sep 1724 Resigned)<ref>Giattini: Ritzler-Sefrin, V, p. 71 with note 6.</ref>\n*Antonio Fonseca (20 Dec 1724 \u2013 9 Dec 1763 Died)<ref>Fonseca: Ritzler-Sefrin, V, p. 71 with note 7.</ref>\n*Ubaldo Baldassini, [[Barnabites|B.]] (1764\u20131786)<ref>Baldassini was born in Jesi in 1700. He lectured in philosophy and theology in houses of the Barnabites, and was Visitor General, Vicar General, and Procurator General. He was named Bishop of Bagnoregio on 16 September 1754, and was transferred to the diocese of Jesi on 9 April 1764 by [[Pope Clement XIII]]. He died in 1786, a little before 2 February. Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 68 with note 2, 113 with note 2.</ref>\n: ''Sede vacante'' (1786\u20131794)<ref>Gams, p. 701, column 1.</ref>\n*Cardinal Giovanni Battista Bussi de Pretis (1794\u20131800)<ref>Bussi de Pretis held the degree of ''[[Doctor of both laws|Doctor in utroque iure]]'' from the University of Urbino. He held the posts of Governor of Narni (1748); Governor of S. Severino (1754);  Governor of Benevento; Governor of Spoleto (1758); Governor of Ascoli (1762); Governor of Ancona (1764); Governor of Civitavecchia (1765); Governor of Frosinone (1766). had been Dean of the Clerics of the Apostolic Camera in the Papal Curia. He was appointed a cardinal at the age of 73 by [[Pope Pius VI]] on 21 February 1794, the same day on which he was named Bishop of Jesi. He participated in the Conclave of 1799\u20131800, which was held in Venice due to the occupation of the Papal States by the French and the Neapolitans. He died in Jesi on 27 June 1800. Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 68 with note 3.</ref>\n\n===since 1800===\n*Cardinal [[Giovanni Battista Caprara]] (11 Aug 1800 \u2013 24 May 1802)<ref>Appointed [[Archbishop of Milan]].</ref>\n*Antonio Maria Odescalchi (28 May 1804 \u2013 23 Jul 1812 Died)\n:''Sede vacante'' (1812\u20131817)\n*Cardinal [[Francesco Cesarei Leoni]] (28 Jul 1817 \u2013 25 Jul 1830 Died)<ref>Leoni was a native of Perugia. He was Dean of the Sacred Roman Rota from June 1809 to 1817. He was named a cardinal by [[Pope Pius VII]] in the consistory of 28 July 1817, and on the same day appointed Bishop of Jesi. {{cite book|author=Philippe Boutry|title=Souverain et pontife: recherches prosopographiques sur la curie romaine \u00e0 l'\u00e2ge de la restauration (1814-1846)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5iJmAAAAMAAJ|year=2002|publisher=\u00c9cole fran\u00e7aise de Rome|location=Rome & Paris|language=French|isbn=978-2-7283-0666-4|pages=170, 345}}</ref>\n*Francesco Tiberi Contigliano (2 Jul 1832 \u2013 18 May 1836 Resigned)\n*Cardinal [[Pietro Ostini]] (1836\u20131841)<ref>Born in Rome in 1775, Ostini had been Professor of Church History at the Collegio Romano. He served as Internuncio at Vienna from 1824 to 1827. He was named titular Archbishop of Tarsus on 9 April 1827, and consecrated by Cardinal Giacomo Giustiniani. After serving as Nuncio in Lucerne in 1828 and Brazil in 1829\u20131831, he returned to Vienna as Nuncio in 1832\u20131836. He was named a cardinal in the consistory of 30 September 1831 by [[Pope Gregory XVI]], but the appointment was kept secret until the day that he was transferred to the diocese of Jesi on 11 July 1836. He resigned the diocese of Jesi on 19 December 1841. He died in Naples on 5 March 1849. {{cite book|title=Diario di Roma|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tjEOAAAAQAAJ&pg=PT121|volume=Anno 1827, Numero 65 (Agosto)|date=1827|publisher=Cracas|location=Roma|language=Italian|page=1}} {{cite book|editor=Gaetano Moroni |title=Dizionario di erudizione storico-ecclesiastica|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hEbxe8NEAQkC&pg=PA56|volume=Vol. L|year=1851|publisher=Tipografia Emiliana|location=Venezia|language=Italian|pages=56\u201357}} {{cite book|author=Joseph Wolff|title=Travels and Adventures of Joseph Wolff|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EWVCAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA69|volume=Vol. I|year=1860|publisher=Saunders, Otley|location=London|pages=69\u201371}} {{cite book|author=Alan J. Reinerman|title=Austria and the Papacy in the Age of Metternich: Revolution and reaction, 1830-1838|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XclKAQAAMAAJ|year=1989|publisher=Catholic University of America Press|isbn=978-0-8132-0548-9|pages=233\u2013237, 272\u2013274, 396}} {{cite book|author=Giuseppe De Marchi|title=Le nunziature apostoliche dal 1800 al 1956|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cRz3tzdEXGwC&pg=PA75|year=1957|publisher=Ed. di Storia e Letteratura|location=Roma|language=Italian|pages=46, 75, 244}} Ritzler-Sefrin, VII, pp. 61, 360.</ref>\n*Cardinal [[Silvestro Belli]] (1842\u20131844)<ref>Born of a patrician family of Anagni in 1781, Belli completed his studies in philosophy at the seminary of Anagni at the age of fourteen. He completed his theological courses at the age of eighteen, and was named secretary of Bishop Giovanni Devoti. Bishop Tosi made him a Canon of the cathedral Chapter. He taught philosophy in the junior seminary until 1817, and became its Rector. Following the death of his brother Francesco in 1818, he obtained the position of ''Sommista'' at the Congregation of the Propaganda, where he became familiar with the Prefect, Cardinal Cappellari, later [[Pope Gregory XVI]]. In 1823 he was secretary of the extraordinary Papal Commission sent to Holland under Cardinal Nasalli. Under the new pope, [[Pope Leo XII|Leo XII]], he was appointed a ''Beneficiatus'' of the Vatican Basilica, and at the same time became Auditor of Cardinal Nasalli. [[Pope Pius VIII]] named him Privy Chamberlain and ''Guardaroba'' in 1829, then Domestic Prelate (monsignor), and then ''Luogotenente Civile'' in the Vicariate of Rome. Gregory XVI named him Delegate in Benevento, then delegate in Orvieto, and in July 1832 President of the Province of Fermo, where he served for two years. On his return to Rome he was promoted Canon of the Vatican Basilica, and in 1834 was named Substitute Secretary of State for Internal Affairs, where he served for four years. He was appointed Secretary of the Consistorial Congregation in 1836, which made him Secretary of the College of Cardinals as well. In 1839, he was appointed Assessor of the Congregation of the Universal and Roman Inquisition. He was named a cardinal on 14 December 1840, but the fact was not made public until 12 July 1841; he was assigned the [[titular church]] of [[Santa Balbina]]. He was appointed Bishop of Jesi on 24 January 1842, and was consecrated in Rome on 24 February by Cardinal Carlo Pedicini. He died in Jesi on 9 September 1844, after a long illness. {{cite book|author=Vincenzo Sabbatini|title=Societ\u00e0 di Agricoltura Jesina. Annali ed Atti|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pYzrptsDhqcC&pg=PA284|volume=Vol. II|year=1844|location=Jesi|language=Italian|pages=277\u2013284|chapter=Cenno sulla vita del Cardinale Silvestro Belli}}</ref>\n*Cardinal [[Cosimo Corsi]] (1845\u20131853)<ref>Corsi was a native of Florence, son of  Marquis Giuseppe Antonio Corsi and Countess Maddalena della Gherardesca. He held the degree of ''[[Doctor of both laws|Doctor in utroque iure]]'' and theology from the University of Rome, La Sapienza (1818). He was named a cardinal in the Consistory of 24 January 1842, and assigned the [[titular church]] of Saints John and Paul. He was appointed Bishop of Jesi on 20 January 1845. On 19 Dec 1853 Corsi was appointed [[Archbishop of Pisa]]. He was imprisoned for two months, for having refused to celebrate a ''Te Deum'' in honor of the new King of Italy, Vittorio Emanuele II. He died on 7 October 1870. {{cite book|title=Relazione autentica dell'arresto del card. Cosimo Corsi arcivescovo di Pisa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nwuh1FkbA9wC&pg=PP7|year=1860|publisher=Gio. Fassi-Como|location=Genoa|language=Italian}} {{cite book|author=Aldo-Luigi Brogialdi|title=Il buon pastore o il cardinale Cosimo Corsi arcivescovo di Pisa parole dette... ne' funerali solenni celebrati da' cattolici pisani in s. Eufrasia il 12 novembre 1870|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C-4Dwo30bTwC&pg=PA17|year=1870|publisher=Tip.  G. Alisi|location=Pisa|language=Italian}} Mauro Del Corso (1988), ''Un vescovo nella storia: Cosimo Corsi, cardinale di Pisa, la storia di un vescovo'' (Pisa: Pacini 1988). Ritzler-Sefrin, VII, pp. 33, 61.</ref>\n*Cardinal [[Carlo Luigi Morichini]] (23 Jun 1854 \u20131871)<ref>On 24 Nov 1871 Cardinal Morichini was transferred to the diocese of  [[Archbishop of Bologna|Bologna]] by [[Pope Pius IX]].</ref>\n*Rambaldo Magagnini (1872\u20131892)<ref>Rambaldo Magagnini was born in Jesi in 1807. He held the degree of ''[[Doctor of both laws|Doctor in utroque iure]]'' and theology from the University of Rome, La Sapienza. He had previously been Prior of the cathedral Chapter of Jesi, and pro-Vicar-General of the diocese. He was named bishop of Jesi on 6 May 1872. He died on 21 December 1892. {{cite book|title=Roma 6 maggio 1872 provvista di chiese|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rJyxPntcYK8C&pg=PP10|year=1872|location=Rome|language=Italian|page=4}} {{cite book|title=La Gerarchia Cattolica e la Famiglia Pontificia: 1875|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y9mQwe5I5cwC|year=1875|publisher=Monaldi|location=Roma|language=Italian|page=211}}</ref>\n*Aurelio Zonghi (12 Jun 1893 \u2013 9 Jan 1902 Resigned)\n*Giovanni Battista Ricci (9 Jun 1902 \u2013 21 Jul 1906 Appointed, [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Ancona-Osimo|Archbishop of Ancona e Numana]])\n*Giuseppe Gandolfi (1 Dec 1906 \u2013 14 Sep 1927 Died)\n*Goffredo Zaccherini (15 Jun 1928 \u2013 11 May 1934 Resigned)\n*Carlo Falcinelli (6 Sep 1934 \u2013 6 Nov 1952 Resigned)\n*Giovanni Battista Pardini (7 Jan 1953 \u2013 30 Apr 1975 Resigned)\n*Oscar Serfilippi, [[O.F.M. Conv.]] (1 Mar 1978 \u2013 20 Mar 2006 Retired)<ref>Serfilippi was born in Mondolfo in 1929. He was a parish priest between 1958 and 1970. He was elected Minister Provincial of the Province of March of the Conventual Franciscans. On 3 September 1975 he was appointed titular bishop of Massula and Auxiliary Bishop of Ancona-Numana. He was named Auxiliary Bishop of Jesi on 1977, and on 1 March 1978 he became Bishop of Jesi. He died on 20 May 2006, two months after his resignation of the bishopric. ''Find a Grave'', [https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/27651687/oscar-serfilippi \"Rev. Oscar Serfilippi\"]; retrieved: 9 March 2019.</ref>\n*Gerardo Rocconi (20 Mar 2006 \u2013 present)<ref>Rocconi was born at Corinaldo (Ancona) in 1949. From 1968 to 1973 he studied philosophy and theology  at the regional seminary in Fano and Ancona. He was ordained a priest for the diocese of Senigallia in 1973, where, from 1973 to 1986 he was Vice-Rector and then Rector of the seminary of Senigallia. From 1985 to 1997 he was a parish priest in Chiaravalle, and from 1992 to 1997 he was Vicar General of the diocese of Senigallia. He was named Bishop of Jesi by [[Pope Benedict XVI]] on 20 March 2006, and consecrated a bishop on 29 April 2006. CV: Diocesi di Jesi, [http://www.jesi.chiesacattolica.it/vescovo.html \"Il vescovo: S.E. Mons. Gerardo Rocconi\"]; retrieved: 28 February 2019. {{in lang|it}}</ref>\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*Diocesi di Jesi, [http://www.jesi.chiesacattolica.it/diocesi.html ''Guida diocesana 2018''] (Press the gray bar entitled \"Scarica la Guida Diocesana\"); retrieved: 5 March 2019.\n\n==Bibliography==\n===Reference works for bishops===\n*{{cite book|last=Gams|first=Pius Bonifatius |title=Series episcoporum Ecclesiae catholicae: quotquot innotuerunt a beato Petro apostolo|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=os9DAQAAMAAJ|year=1873|publisher=Typis et Sumptibus Georgii Josephi Manz|location=Ratisbon|language=Latin}} pp.&nbsp;700\u2013701.\n*{{cite book|last1=Eubel|first1=Conradus (ed.)|last2=Gulik|first2=Guilelmus|title=Hierarchia catholica|volume= Tomus 3|date=1923|publisher=Libreria Regensbergiana|language=Latin|location=M\u00fcnster|edition=second|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol02eubeuoft}} \n*{{cite book|last1=Gauchat|first1=Patritius (Patrice)|title=Hierarchia catholica|volume=Tomus IV (1592-1667)|date=1935|publisher=Libraria Regensbergiana|location=M\u00fcnster|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol04eubeuoft}} \n*{{cite book|last1=Ritzler|first1=Remigius|last2=Sefrin|first2=Pirminus|title=Hierarchia catholica medii et recentis aevi|volume=Tomus V (1667-1730)|date=1952|publisher=Messagero di S. Antonio|location=Patavii|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol05eubeuoft}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Ritzler|first1=Remigius|last2=Sefrin|first2=Pirminus|title=Hierarchia catholica medii et recentis aevi|volume=Tomus VI (1730-1799)|date=1958|publisher=Messagero di S. Antonio|location=Patavii|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol06eubeuoft}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Ritzler|first1=Remigius|last2=Sefrin|first2=Pirminus|title=Hierarchia Catholica medii et recentioris aevi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pgyItwAACAAJ|volume=Volume VII (1800\u20131846)|year=1968|publisher=Libreria Regensburgiana|location=Monasterii|language=Latin}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Remigius Ritzler|author2=Pirminus Sefrin|title=Hierarchia catholica Medii et recentioris aevi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5oXUjwEACAAJ|year=1978|volume=Volume VIII (1846\u20131903)|publisher=Il Messaggero di S. Antonio|language=Latin}}\n*{{cite book|last= Pi\u0119ta|first=Zenon|title=Hierarchia catholica medii et recentioris aevi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QXuJQwAACAAJ|volume=Volume IX (1903\u20131922)|year=2002|publisher=Messagero di San Antonio|location=Padua|language=Latin|isbn=978-88-250-1000-8}}\n\n===Studies===\n*{{cite book|last=Baldassini|first=Girolamo|title=Memorie istoriche dell'antichissima e regia citt\u00e0 di Jesi|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_7lAc3Ka1T9MC|year=1765|publisher=Pietropaolo Bonelli|location=Jesi|language=Italian|pages=361\u2013382}}\n*{{cite book|last=Cappelletti|first=Giuseppe|title=Le chiese d'Italia della loro origine sino ai nostri giorni|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vtICAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA195|volume=Volume settimo|year=1848|publisher=G. Antonelli|location=Venezia|language=Italian|pages=271\u2013320}}\n*Lanzoni, Francesco (1927). ''[https://archive.org/stream/MN5017ucmf_0#page/n281/mode/2up Le diocesi d'Italia dalle origini al principio del secolo VII (an. 604)]''. Faenza: F. Lega, pp.&nbsp;490\u2013492. {{in lang|it}}\n*Mezzadri, L; Tagliaferri, M; Guerriero, E. (eds) (2008), ''Le diocesi d'Italia'' Volume III (Torino, San Paolo edizioni, 2008). {{in lang|it}}\n*{{cite book|last=Stefani|first=G.|title=Dizionario corografico dello Stato Pontificio|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QdJoAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA575|year=1856|publisher=Presso gli Stabilimenti di Civelli G. e C.|location=Milano e Verona|language=Italian|pages=506\u2013515}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Ughelli|first1=Ferdinando|last2=Coleti|first2=Niccol\u00f2|title=Italia sacra, sive De Episcopis Italiae|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zTkOnHgYhFgC|volume=Tomus primus|edition=secunda|year=1717|publisher=apud Sebastianum Coleti|location=Venice|language=Latin|pages=279\u2013287}}\n\n====Acknowledgment====\n::{{Catholic|title=Jesi}}\n\n{{Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of Ancona-Osimo}}\n\n{{coord|43.3561|N|13.2439|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses in le Marche|Iesi]]\n[[Category:Dioceses established in the 6th century|Iesi]]\n[[Category:Iesi|Diocese]]\n[[Category:6th-century establishments in Italy]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox diocese\n| jurisdiction      = Diocese<!-- Type of jurisdiction: i.e. Diocese or Archdiocese -->\n| name              = Iesi\n| latin             = Dioecesis Aesina\n| local             = <!-- Name in the native language -->\n| image             = Jesi-SanSettimio.jpg\n| image_size        = 255px\n| image_alt         = \n| caption           = Cathedral in [[Iesi]]\n<!---- Locations ---->\n| country           = Italy\n| metropolitan      =  \n| territory         = \n| province          = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Ancona-Osimo|Ancona-Osimo]]\n| coordinates       = <!-- Use {{coord}} -->\n<!---- Statistics ---->\n| area_km2          = 315\n| population        = 80,930 (est.)\n| population_as_of  = 2016\n| catholics         = 75,300 (guess)<!-- Number of Catholics in the diocese -->\n| catholics_percent = 93.0\n| parishes          = 41<!-- Number of parishes in the diocese -->\n| churches          = <!-- Number of churches in the diocese -->\n| congregations     = <!-- Number of congregations in the diocese -->\n| schools           = <!-- Number of church supported schools in the diocese -->\n| members           = <!-- Number of members in the diocese -->\n<!---- Information ---->\n| denomination      = [[Catholic Church]]\n| rite              = [[Roman Rite]]\n| established       = 6th Century\n| cathedral         = Basilica Cattedrale di S. Settimio\n| cocathedral       = \n| patron            = \n| priests           = 35 (diocesan)<br />23 (Religious Orders)<br />11 Permanent Deacons<!-- Number of priests in the diocese -->\n<!---- Current leadership ---->\n| pope              = {{Incumbent pope}} <!-- DO NOT CHANGE. This will update the Popes Automatically as they change -->\n| bishop_title      = Bishop\n| bishop            = [[Gerardo Rocconi]]\n| coadjutor         = \n| auxiliary_bishops = \n| vicar_general     = \n| emeritus_bishops  = \n<!---- Map ---->\n| map               = Roman Catholic Diocese of Jesi in Italy.jpg\n| map_alt           = Locator map of diocese of Jesi\n| map_caption       = \n<!---- Website ---->\n| website           = [http://www.jesi.chiesacattolica.it/index.html Diocesi di Jesi] {{in lang|it}}\n| footnotes         = \n}}\nThe  '''diocese of [[Iesi]]''' ({{lang-la|Dioecesis Aesina}}) is a Catholic ecclesiastical territory in the [[Marche]], Italy. It is a [[suffragan]] of the [[archdiocese of Ancona-Osimo]].<ref name=CathHierIesi>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/djesi.html \"Diocese of Iesi\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]'' David M. Cheney. Retrieved February 29, 2016. {{Self-published source|date=March 2019}}</ref><ref name=GCathIesi>[http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/jesi0.htm \"Diocese of Jesi\"] ''GCatholic.org.'' Gabriel Chow. Retrieved February 29, 2016. {{Self-published source|date=March 2019}}</ref> The diocese itself prefers the spelling Jesi.\n\n==History==\n[[Saint Septimius]], supposedly martyred in 307, has been venerated as the first bishop of [[Jesi]] since the 15th century.<ref>There is no reference to him whatever until 1469. Joannes Periero, S.J., \"De S. Septimio episc. et mart.\", in: ''Acta Sanctorum Septembris'' Tomus VI (Antwerp: Bernard vander Plassche 1757), pp. 408-410.</ref> [[Saint Florianus]], who was cast into the [[Esino]] in the [[Diocletian persecution]], is also venerated (perhaps he is confounded with Saint Florianus who was cast into the Enus or Anisus). Other bishops of antiquity were Calumniosus (c. 647) and Honestus. Their relics were discovered in 1623.\n\nThe future emperor [[Frederick II, Holy Roman Emperor|Frederick II]] was born in Jesi on 26 December 1194. His mother, [[Constance, Queen of Sicily]], was on her way to join her husband, [[Henry VI, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry VI]], who had been crowned King of Sicily at Palermo on the previous day. At Jesi she was overcome by sudden labor pains, and, anticipating the birth of an heir, the people erected a pavilion for her in the town square, so that the birth might take place amid a large complement of witnesses.<ref>{{cite book|author1=J.L.A. Huillard-Breholles|author2=H. de Albertis de Luynes|title=Historia diplomatica Friderici Secundi. Pr\u00e9face et introduction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BQxYAAAAcAAJ&pg=PP5|year=1859|publisher=Plon|location=Paris|language=French|page=clxxvii}}</ref> Fifteen cardinals and bishops witnessed the birth of the baby Frederick.<ref>Albert of S. Maria in State, ''Annales Stadenses'', in: ''Monumenta Germaniae Historica'', Scriptores XVI (Hannover: Hahn 1859), p. 352.</ref>\n\nOn 30 May 1247, [[Pope Innocent IV]] rejected the election of one of the Canons of the Cathedral Chapter, [[Armannus]], as bishop of Jesi, on the grounds that the Canons were excommunicated due to their support of the Emperor Frederick II. One Canon, however, named Montanario, was loyal to the Holy See and had escaped to Ancona from Jesi; he notified the Pope that he elected the Franciscan Gualterio. Innocent ordered the Rector of the March of Ancona, Marcellino Aretino, and Bishop Philip of Fermo to investigate the election and consult with Canon Montanario, and provide the new bishop. <ref>{{cite book|editor=Rodenberg, Carolus|title=Epistolae saeculi XIII e regestis pontificum Romanorum selectae|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VH0_AQAAMAAJ&pg=RA5-PA71|series=Monumenta Germaniae Historica|volume=Tomus II|year=1887|publisher=Apud Weidmannos|location=Berlin|language=German, Latin|pages=275, no. 373}} Baldassini, p. 57, and ''Appendix'' pp. xviii-xix.</ref> The Franciscan Gualtiero, an Englishman, was appointed. He was a friend of [[John of Parma]], general of the order and patron of the [[Franciscan Spirituals]].<ref>Gualterius is spoken of by Salimbene as \"bonus cantor, bonus praedicator, bonus dictator.\" Fra Salimbene of Parma, ''Chronica Fr. Salimbene Parmensis Ordinis Minorum'' (Parmae : Ex officina Petri Fiaccadorii, 1857), pp. 317-319 (under the year 1284). By ''dictator'', Salimbene means that Gualterius was a good writer.</ref>. \n\nBishop Severinus in 1237 laid the foundations of the new cathedral;<ref>Ughelli, I, p. 282.</ref> the old cathedral, dedicated to Saint Nicholas of Myra, was outside the city, and in the eighteenth century had fallen into ruin.<ref>Baldassini, p. 159.</ref> In its current form, the cathedral is the result of restorations and renovations carried out by Bishop Antonio Fonseca.<ref>Baldaassini, p. 382.</ref>\n\nThe cathedral was and is administered by a Chapter, composed of a Prior and ten Canons.<ref>Cappelletti, p. 313. Ritzler-Sefrin, V, p. 71 note 1; VI, p. 68 note 1. Diocesi di Jesi, [http://www.jesi.chiesacattolica.it/diocesi.html        ''Guida diocesana 2018''] (Press the gray bar entitled \"Scarica la Guida Diocesana\"), page 9; retrieved: 5 March 2019.</ref> Up until the middle of the 15th century the Canons were required to live in the ''Canonica'', unless individually dispensed. Pope Paul II (1464\u20131471) dispensed the Canons from this obligation.<ref>Baldassini, p. 342.</ref> The best-known of the Canons was Marcello Cervini, who became [[Pope Marcellus II]] (1555).<ref>Baldassini, p. 343.</ref>\n\n[[Gabriele del Monte]] (1554) introduced the reforms of the [[Council of Trent]], which he had attended. His successors were Cardinal [[Pope Paul V|Camillo Borghese]] (1597), afterwards Pope Paul V; Cardinals [[Tiberio Cenci]] (1621) and [[Alderano Cybo]] (1656), noted for their benefactions; Bishop Antonio Fonseca (1724), who founded a hospital. [[Cardinal Caprara]], afterwards [[Archbishop of Milan]], who concluded the Concordat with Napoleon, was Bishop of Jesi (1800\u201302). He was succeeded by [[Antonio Odescalchi]], who was deported to Milan by the French in 1809, dying in exile in Cesano Boscone in 1812.<ref>Umberto Benigni (1910), [http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/08372a.htm \"Jesi.\"] ''The Catholic Encyclopedia'' Vol. 8. (New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1910); retrieved: 28 February 2019. {{cite book|editor=Simonetta Bernardi|title=La religione e il trono: Pio VIII nell'Europa del suo tempo : Convegno di studi : Cingoli, 12-13 giugno 1993|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JTfkAAAAMAAJ|year=1995|publisher=La Fenice edizioni|location=Roma|language=Italian|isbn=978-88-86171-14-4|page=7}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 August 1972, by the Bull ''Qui apostolico officio'', [[Pope Paul VI]] created the new ecclesiastical province of Ancona, and granted its archbishop the status of Metropolitan. The ecclesiastical province was assigned the suffragan dioceses of Jesi (Aesina) and Osimo (Auximana).<ref>''Acta Apostolicae Sedis'' [https://www.vatican.va/archive/aas/documents/AAS-64-1972-ocr.pdf An. et Vol. LXIV] (Citt\u00e0 del Vaticano: Typis Polyglottis Vaticanis 1972), pp. 664-665.</ref>\n\n===Synods===\n\nA diocesan synod was an irregularly held, but important, meeting of the bishop of a diocese and his clergy. Its purpose was (1) to proclaim generally the various decrees already issued by the bishop; (2) to discuss and ratify measures on which the bishop chose to consult with his clergy; (3) to publish statutes and decrees of the diocesan synod, of the provincial synod, and of the Holy See.<ref name=\"XIV1842\">{{cite book|author=Benedictus XIV|title=Benedicti XIV ... De Synodo dioecesana libri tredecim|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tj0F8czA8XsC&pg=PA51|volume=Tomus primus|year=1842|publisher=Hanicq|location=Mechlin|language=Latin|pages=42\u201349|chapter=Lib. I. caput secundum. De Synodi Dioecesanae utilitate}} John Paul II, Constitutio Apostolica ''de Synodis Dioecesanis Agendis'' (March 19, 1997): [https://www.vatican.va/archive/aas/documents/AAS-89-1997-ocr.pdf ''Acta Apostolicae Sedis'' 89] (1997), pp. 706-727.</ref>\n\nBishop Marco Agrippa Dandini (1599\u20131603) held a diocesan synod in Jesi on 16 September 1600.<ref>Marco Agrippa Dandini, ''Decreta in Diocesana Synodo Aesina promulgata a perillustr. et Reverendissimo d. d. Marco Agrippa Dandino, Nob. Caesenate Dei et Apostolicae Sedis gratia Episcopo Aesino. Die 16 Septembris 1600'' (Jesi: Petrus de Farris 1600).</ref> Bishop Tiberio Cenci (1621\u20131653) held a synod on 10 May 1626,<ref>''Decreta Synodi dioec. celebratae sub Illustriss. et reverendiss. d. d. Tyberio Cincio, Episc. Aesin., die decima mensis Maij MDCXXVI'' (Jesi: Gregorius Arnazzini 1626). </ref> and, as Cardinal, another synod on 23 September 1649.<ref>''Constitutiones sancitae in synodo dioecesana ab Eminentiss. et Reverendiss. D. D. Tiberio, tit. S. Callisti S. R. E. Presbytero Cardinali, Cincio, Episcopo Aesino, die XXIII septembris M.DC.XXXXIX'' (Fermo: Andrea de Montibus 1649).</ref> Cardinal Alderano Cybo (1656\u20131671) held a diocesan synod in Jesi from 4 to 6 July 1658.<ref>{{cite book|author=Alderano Cybo|title=Ordinationes, et decreta in Synodo \u00c6sina IV. V. et VI Iulii M.DC.LVIII. celebrata, etc|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gld93kmqYVkC&pg=PA223|year=1665|publisher=Apud Franciscum Seraphinum|location=Ancona|language=Latin}}</ref> Cardinal Pietro Matteo Petrucci held his first diocesan synod on 26\u201428 April 1683. He held his second diocesan synod in Jesi on 21 March 1695.<ref name=\"Jesi1695\">{{cite book|author=Pietro Matteo Petrucci|title=Secunda dioecesana aesina Synodus ab eminentiss. ac reuerendiss. d. d. Petro Matthaeo S.R.E. card. Petruccio ... In sua cathedrali ecclesia celebrata anno 1695|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S37Sa5GNyzcC&pg=PP1|year=1695|publisher=typis Heredum Pannelli, & Angeli Antonij Monticelli|location=Macerata|language=Latin}} J.-D. Mansi (ed.), ''Sacrorum Conciliorum nova et amplissima collectio'', editio novissima, Tomus XXXVI<sup>ter</sup> (Arnhem & Leipzig: H. Welter 1924), pp. 469, 495, 659.</ref>\n\nOn 23 April 1708, Bishop Alessandro Fedele (1696\u20131715) held a diocesan synod, whose decisions were published in 1713.<ref>''Synodus dioecesana ab illustriss. ac Reverendiss. d. Alexandro Fideli, Dei et Apostolicae Sedis Episcopo... in ecclesia cathedrali sub die 23 Aprilis celebrata, anno a reparata salute 1708'' (Jesi: Alexandrelli et Benedicti 1713).</ref> Bishop Antonio Fonseca held a diocesan synod in the Cathedral on 25 to 27 May 1727. The synodal decrees were published.<ref>{{cite book|author=Antonio Fonseca|title=Constitutiones synodales Aesinae ... habitae diebus 25. 26. et 27 mensis Maji 1727|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OARNAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA1|year=1728|publisher=Joh. Bapt. de Julius|location=Jesi|language=Latin}}</ref> He held a second diocesan synod on 26 and 27 September 1741, and its constitutions too were published.<ref>{{cite book|author=Antonio Fonseca|title=Secunda dioecesana Synodus Aesina celebrata diebus 26 et 27 Septembris 1741|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sA5NAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA1|year=1741|publisher=Joannes Bapt. de Julius|location=Jesi|language=Latin}}</ref> From 14 June to 16 June 1772, Bishop Ubaldo Baldassini, B. (1764\u20131786) held a diocesan synod, and published its synodal constitutions.<ref>''Sanctae Aesinae Ecclesiae Synodales Constitutiones ab illustrissimo et reverendissimo domino Domino Ubaldo Baldassino, Dei et Apostolicae Sedis gratia Episcopo Aesino... in dioecesanis comitiis editae diebus XIV, XV, XVI Junii, anno reparatae slautis MDCCLXXII'' (Jesi: Pietro Paolo Bonelli 1772).</ref>\n\nCardinal Carlo Luigi Morichini (1854\u20131871) presided over a diocesan synod on 15\u201417 November 1857.<ref>''Synodus dioecesana ab Eminentissimo et Reverendissimo Domino Carolo Aloysio Tituli S. Onuphrii S. R. E. Presbytero Cardinali Morichini Archipeiscopo Episcopo Aesino, celebrata in Ecclesia Cathedrali diebus xv, xvi, xvii novembris MDCCCLVII.'' (Aesii: Vincentius Cherubini 1857).</ref>\n\nBishop Oscar Serfilippi (1978\u20132006) held a diocesan synod in Jesi on 24 January 1982.<ref>''Find a Grave'', [https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/27651687/oscar-serfilippi \"Rev. Oscar Serfilippi\"]; retrieved: 9 March 2019.</ref>\n\n==Bishops of Iesi==\n===to 1100===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n:'''...''' \n: ? Septimius<ref>There is no reference to Septimius before 1469. Lanzoni, pp. 491-492: ''Prima del 1469 nessuna carta, nessuna memoria, nessun monumento di Iesi parla di un s. Settimio venerato nella cattedrale o in altro luogo; e la stessa cattedrale non era denominata da lui, ma dal SS. Salvatore''....</ref>\n:'''...''' \n:[Martianus (501)]<ref>Martianus is listed as a bishop of Jesi by Gams, p. 700, but Lanzoni, p. 492, points out that he was actually Bishop of Aeca (Aecanus, not Aesinus).</ref>\n:'''...''' \n*Calompiosus (c. 647)<ref>He is also called Calcompios and Calumniosus. Gams, p. 700.</ref>\n*Honestus (attested 680)<ref>Gams, p. 700. J.-D. Mansi (ed.), ''Sacrorum Conciliorum nova et amplissima collectio'', editio novissima, Tomus XI (Florence: A. Zatta 1773), p. 773.</ref>\n\n*Petrus (attested 743)<ref>Bishop Petrus was present at the first Roman synod of [[Pope Zacharias]]. Ughelli, I, p. 282. J.-D. Mansi (ed.), ''Sacrorum Conciliorum nova et amplissima collectio'', editio novissima, Tomus XII (Florence: A. Zatta 1776), p. 384c: ''Petrus Esis'', ''Petro Esino''.</ref>\n:'''...''' \n*Anastasius (attested 853)<ref>Bishop Anastasius did not attend the Roman synod of [[Pope Leo IV]] of 853, but he sent his deacon, Aimo, to represent him. J.-D. Mansi (ed.), ''Sacrorum Conciliorum nova et amplissima collectio'', editio novissima, Tomus XIV (Venice: A. Zatta 1769), p. 1020. Cappelletti, VII, p. 277.</ref>\n:'''...''' \n*Eberhard (attested 967)<ref>Bishop Eberhard was present at the Synod of Ravenna on 25 April 967. Gerhard Schwartz (1907), [https://archive.org/details/MN42020ucmf_1 ''Die Besetzung der Bist\u00fcmer Reichsitaliens unter den s\u00e4chsischen und salischen Kaisern: mit den Listen der Bisch\u00f6fe, 951-1122'']. Leipzig: B.G. Teubner. p.&nbsp;247. (in German)</ref>\n:'''...''' \n:[Martianus (attested 1027)]<ref>Martianus was Bishop of Cesena, not Jesi. Schwartz, p. 247, note 1. Detlev Jasper, [http://daten.digitale-sammlungen.de/~db/0009/bsb00096352/images/index.html?id=00096352&nativeno=93 ''Die Konzilien Deutschlands und Reichsitaliens 1023 - 1059''] [[MGH Concilia VIII] (Hannover: Hahn 2010), p. 93.</ref>\n:'''...''' \n{{Div col end}}\n===from 1100 to 1500===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*Raynaldus (1164\u20131175)<ref>Gams, p. 700.</ref>\n*Grimoaldus\n*Crescentius (attested 1207)<ref>Baldassini, p. 367. Gams, p. 700. Eubel, ''Hierarchia catholica'' I, p. 75</ref>\n*Philippus<ref>Philippus: Cappelletti, VII, p. 279.</ref>\n*Severinus (attested 1230, 1235, 1237)<ref>Severinus is named in an inscription of 1237 on a marble plaque above the main door of the cathedral. Ughelli, p. 282. Cappelletti, VII, p. 279.</ref>\n:Armannus (Hermannus)<ref>Armannus was never more than an intrusive bishop-elect. He was elected by the Cathedral Chapter, but the Chapter had been excommunicated and had no right to participate in an election. His election was quashed by Pope Innocent IV on 30 May 1247. {{cite book|editor=Rodenberg, Carolus|title=Epistolae saeculi XIII e regestis pontificum Romanorum selectae|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VH0_AQAAMAAJ&pg=RA5-PA71|series=Monumenta Germaniae Historica|volume=Tomus II|year=1887|publisher=Apud Weidmannos|location=Berlin|language=German, Latin|pages=275, no. 373}}</ref>\n*Gualterus, O.Min.\n*Crescentius (1252\u20131263)<ref>Eubel, I, p. 75.</ref>\n*Bonajuncta, O.Min. (1263\u20131267)\n*Hugo (1267\u2013 )\n*Ioannes (1289\u20131295)<ref>Ioannes: Gams, p. 700 column 2. Eubel, I, p. 75.</ref>\n*Leonardus (1295\u20131311)<ref>Leonardo: Gams, p. 700 column 2. Eubel, I, p. 75.</ref>\n*Francesco Alfani (1312\u20131342)<ref>Francesco: Gams, p. 700 column 2. Eubel, I, p. 75.</ref>\n*Francesco Jordani Brancaleoni (1342\u20131350)<ref>Francesco was a native of Spoleto. He was appointed Bishop of Jesi by [[Pope Clement VI]] on 18 July 1342. Gams, p. 700 column 2. Eubel, I, p. 75.</ref>\n*Nicolaus de Pisis, O.E.S.A. (1350\u2013c. 1370)<ref>Bishop Nicolaus was still in office in 1361. Cappelletti, p. 288. Eubel, I, p. 75, states that he served until his death, but does not give a date.</ref>\n*Giovanni Zeminiani Rizardi, O.P. (1371\u20131373)\n*Berardus de Beysiaco, O.E.S.A. (1373\u20131391?)<ref>Ughelli, I, p. 283, calls him Bernardus, and states that he died in 1391.</ref>\n*? Pietro Borghese (? attested c. 1380)<ref>Pietro is said to have belonged to the famous Sienese family. He may have been intruded during the Western Schism. Knowledge of him comes only from an entry in Prospero Mendosio, citing an entry in Ugurgerio's ''De ponpis Senensibus'', who quotes from a genealogical work on the family by Celsus Cittadinus. Ughelli, pp. 282-283. Baldassini, p. 370.</ref>\n*Tommaso Pierleone (1391\u20131400)<ref>Pierleone had been elected bishop of Ascoli Piceno in 1390, and was still bishop-elect when transferred to Jesi on 12 July 1391 by [[Pope Boniface IX]]. He resigned the bishopric in 1400, in order to enter the monastery of [[San Lorenzo fuori le mura]] in Rome. Baldassari, pp. 370-371. Ughelli, p. 283. Eubel, I, pp. 75, 111.</ref>\n*Ludovico (Aloysius) Francisci Alfani (1400\u20131405)<ref>Luigi Alfani was appointed on 2 June 1400 by [[Pope Boniface IX]] of the Roman Obedience in the Western Schism. He had been abbot of the monastery of S. Paolo on the Arno in the diocese of Pisa. Baldassini, p. 371. Eubel, I, p. 75.</ref>\n*Jacobus Bonriposi (1405\u20131418)<ref>Bonriposi was appointed on 7 October 1405 by [[Pope Innocent VII]] of the Roman Obedience in the Western Schism. He was transferred to the diocese of Narni by [[Pope Martin V]] on 31 January 1418. He died in 1455. Baldassini, p. 371. Eubel, I, p. 75, 357.</ref>\n*Blondus Conchi (1418\u2013 )\n*Lazarus ( ? \u20131425)\n*[[Innocenzo de Comite]] (30 May 1425 \u2013 1443)<ref>Eubel, I, p. 75.</ref>\n:'''...''' \n*[[Thomas Ghisleri]] (5 Oct 1463 \u20131505)<ref>Ghislieri died on 6 June 1505. Baldassini, p. 372. Eubel, ''Hierarchia catholica'' II, p. 81 with note 1.</ref>\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===from 1500 to 1800===\n*Angelo Ripanti (1505\u20131513)<ref>Ripanti: Eubel, ''Hierarchia catholica'' III, p. 97.</ref>\n*Pietro Paolo Venanzio (1513\u20131519)<ref>Venanzio was appointed on 2 September 1513. He served until 1519. Eubel, III, p. 97.</ref>\n*Antonio de Spello (1519\u20131540)<ref>Spello: Eubel, III, p. 97.</ref>\n*[[Benedetto Conversini]] (1540\u20131553)<ref>A native of Pistoia, Conversini was Rector of the University of Pisa in 1518. He was Vice-Legate in Viterbo, and served as Bishop of Bertinoro (Veneto) from 1537 to 1540. On 21 March 1538 he was named Governor of the city of Rome and Vice-Chamberlain, a position he held for five years. He was transferred to the diocese of Jesi by [[Pope Paul III]] on 10 June 1540. During this time he was also Governor of Bologna, and President of the Romagna. He died at Castel del Piano (Jesi) in June 1553. {{cite book|author=Enrico Binde|title=Notizia biografica di Monsignor Benedetto Conversini, Pistoiese, Vescovo d'Iesi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C5NeAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA19|year=1851|publisher=Ranieri Guasti|location=Prato|language=Italian|page=19}} {{cite book|author=Vittorio Capponi|title=Biografia pistoiese|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kIbqYIeoNgMC&pg=PA136|year=1883|publisher=Tipografia Rossetti|location=Pistoia|language=Italian|pages=136\u2013138}} Eubel, III, pp. 97, 139 with note 5.</ref>\n*[[Gabriele Del Monte]] (10 Nov 1554 \u2013 27 Apr 1597 Died)<ref>Del Monte was the grand-nephew of [[Pope Julius III]], and the nephew of Cardinal Cristoforo Ciocchi del Monte. He participated in the [[Council of Trent]], and in accordance with its decrees, he founded the diocesan seminary. Cappelletti, VII, pp. 300-301. {{cite book|author=Ciro Zenobi|title=L' Episcopato Jesino di Monsignore Gabriele del Monte: (1554-1597)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EYjNNAEACAAJ|year=1979|publisher=Pontifical Lateran University|location=Rome|language=Italian}}</ref>\n*[[Pope Paul V|Camillo Borghese]] (1597\u20131599)<ref>Borghese was appointed Bishop of Jesi in the papal Consistory of 14 April 1597. He resigned the See on 2 August 1599. Gauchat, ''Hierarchia catholica'' IV, p. 71.</ref>\n*[[Marco Agrippa Dandini]] (1599\u20131603 Died)<ref>A native of Cesena, Dandini was appointed Bishop of Jesi by [[Pope Clement VIII]] on 2 August 1599. He died in Cesena on 20 October 1603 at the age of forty-six. Ughelli, I, p. 285. Gauchat, p. 71.</ref>\n*[[Pirro Imperoli]] (1604\u20131617)<ref>Imperioli had been Auditor and Vicar General of Cardinal Borghese when he was Bishop of Jesi. He was the first Canon Penitentiary of the Cathedral Chapter. He was named Bishop of Jesi by [[Pope Clement VIII]] on 28 January 1604. {{cite book|title=Studia Picena|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LNJ4Pw9dsbwC|year=1939|publisher=Pontificio Seminario marchigiano Pio 11.|location=Fano|language=Italian|page=143}} Cappelletti, VII, p. 302. Gauchat, p. 71 with note 4.</ref>\n*[[Marcello Pignatelli]], [[Theatines|C.R.]] (13 Nov 1617 \u2013 1621 Died)<ref>Cappelletti, VII, p. 302. Gauchat, p. 71 with note 5.</ref>\n*[[Tiberio Cenci]] (1621\u20131653)<ref>Cenci was a Roman, the nephew of Cardinal Marcello Lante. He held the degree ''[[Doctor of both laws|Doctor in utroque iure]]'', and was a Referendary of the Tribunal of the Two Signatures. In 1612 he was Governor of Jesi. He was named Bishop of Jesi in the papal consistory of 24 November 1621; there is no record of his consecration. On 20 April 1622 Cenci was named Governor of Loreto by [[Pope Gregory XV]]. In 1623 he discovered the purported remains of Saint Septimius. He was appointed a cardinal on 6 March 1645. He died on 26 February 1653, at the age of 73, according to his funeral inscription in the cathedral of Jesi. Cappelletti, p. 303. Gauchat, p. 71 with note 6.</ref>\n*Cardinal [[Giacomo Corradi]] (21 Apr 1653 \u2013 Apr 1656 Resigned)<ref>A native of Ferrara, Corradi had been  He was named a cardinal by [[Pope Innocent X]] on 19 February 1652, and was appointed to the [[titular church]] of S. Maria trans Tiberim. He  was appointed bishop of Jesi in the consistory of 21 April 1653, and was consecrated a bishop by Cardinal Fabio Chigi on 1 May 1553. On 10 April 1655, he was appointed pro-Datary of His Holiness, which required his residence in Rome; he held the post until his death. He died in Rome on 17 January 1666. Baldassini, pp. 377-378. Gauchat, pp. 30 no. 27, with notes 1 and 2; 71 with note 7.</ref>\n*[[Alderano Cibo]] (24 Apr 1656 \u2013 10 Dec 1671 Resigned)\n*[[Lorenzo Cibo]] (Cybo) (18 Jan 1671 \u2013 17 Aug 1680 Died)<ref>Cibo: Ritzler-Sefrin, ''Hierarchia catholica'' V, p. 71 with note 3.</ref>\n*[[Pier Matteo Petrucci]], [[Oratory of Saint Philip Neri|C.O.]] (14 Apr 1681 \u20131695/1696)<ref>Petrucci was still bishop when he held his second diocesan synod in Jesi on 21 March 1695. {{cite book|author=Pietro Matteo Petrucci|title=Secunda dioecesana aesina Synodus ab eminentiss. ac reuerendiss. d. d. Petro Matthaeo S.R.E. card. Petruccio ... In sua cathedrali ecclesia celebrata anno 1695|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S37Sa5GNyzcC&pg=PP1|year=1695|publisher=typis Heredum Pannelli, & Angeli Antonij Monticelli|location=Macerata|language=Latin}} J.-D. Mansi (ed.), ''Sacrorum Conciliorum nova et amplissima collectio'', editio novissima, Tomus XXXVI<sup>ter</sup> (Arnhem & Leipzig: H. Welter 1924), pp. 469, 495, 659. Ritzler-Sefrin, V, p. 71 with note 4.</ref>\n*[[Alessandro Fedele]] (20 Feb 1696 \u2013 7 Apr 1715 Died)<ref>Fedele: Ritzler-Sefrin, V, p. 71 with note 5.</ref>\n*Francesco Antonio Giattini (7 Dec 1716 \u2013 27 Sep 1724 Resigned)<ref>Giattini: Ritzler-Sefrin, V, p. 71 with note 6.</ref>\n*Antonio Fonseca (20 Dec 1724 \u2013 9 Dec 1763 Died)<ref>Fonseca: Ritzler-Sefrin, V, p. 71 with note 7.</ref>\n*Ubaldo Baldassini, [[Barnabites|B.]] (1764\u20131786)<ref>Baldassini was born in Jesi in 1700. He lectured in philosophy and theology in houses of the Barnabites, and was Visitor General, Vicar General, and Procurator General. He was named Bishop of Bagnoregio on 16 September 1754, and was transferred to the diocese of Jesi on 9 April 1764 by [[Pope Clement XIII]]. He died in 1786, a little before 2 February. Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 68 with note 2, 113 with note 2.</ref>\n: ''Sede vacante'' (1786\u20131794)<ref>Gams, p. 701, column 1.</ref>\n*Cardinal Giovanni Battista Bussi de Pretis (1794\u20131800)<ref>Bussi de Pretis held the degree of ''[[Doctor of both laws| Doctor in utroque iure]]'' from the University of Urbino. He held the posts of Governor of Narni (1748); Governor of S. Severino (1754);  Governor of Benevento; Governor of Spoleto (1758); Governor of Ascoli (1762); Governor of Ancona (1764); Governor of Civitavecchia (1765); Governor of Frosinone (1766). had been Dean of the Clerics of the Apostolic Camera in the Papal Curia. He was appointed a cardinal at the age of 73 by [[Pope Pius VI]] on 21 February 1794, the same day on which he was named Bishop of Jesi. He participated in the Conclave of 1799\u20131800, which was held in Venice due to the occupation of the Papal States by the French and the Neapolitans. He died in Jesi on 27 June 1800. Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 68 with note 3.</ref>\n\n===since 1800===\n*Cardinal [[Giovanni Battista Caprara]] (11 Aug 1800 \u2013 24 May 1802)<ref>Appointed [[Archbishop of Milan]].</ref>\n*Antonio Maria Odescalchi (28 May 1804 \u2013 23 Jul 1812 Died)\n:''Sede vacante'' (1812\u20131817)\n*Cardinal [[Francesco Cesarei Leoni]] (28 Jul 1817 \u2013 25 Jul 1830 Died)<ref>Leoni was a native of Perugia. He was Dean of the Sacred Roman Rota from June 1809 to 1817. He was named a cardinal by [[Pope Pius VII]] in the consistory of 28 July 1817, and on the same day appointed Bishop of Jesi. {{cite book|author=Philippe Boutry|title=Souverain et pontife: recherches prosopographiques sur la curie romaine \u00e0 l'\u00e2ge de la restauration (1814-1846)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5iJmAAAAMAAJ|year=2002|publisher=\u00c9cole fran\u00e7aise de Rome|location=Rome & Paris|language=French|isbn=978-2-7283-0666-4|pages=170, 345}}</ref>\n*Francesco Tiberi Contigliano (2 Jul 1832 \u2013 18 May 1836 Resigned)\n*Cardinal [[Pietro Ostini]] (1836\u20131841)<ref>Born in Rome in 1775, Ostini had been Professor of Church History at the Collegio Romano. He served as Internuncio at Vienna from 1824 to 1827. He was named titular Archbishop of Tarsus on 9 April 1827, and consecrated by Cardinal Giacomo Giustiniani. After serving as Nuncio in Lucerne in 1828 and Brazil in 1829\u20131831, he returned to Vienna as Nuncio in 1832\u20131836. He was named a cardinal in the consistory of 30 September 1831 by [[Pope Gregory XVI]], but the appointment was kept secret until the day that he was transferred to the diocese of Jesi on 11 July 1836. He resigned the diocese of Jesi on 19 December 1841. He died in Naples on 5 March 1849. {{cite book|title=Diario di Roma|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tjEOAAAAQAAJ&pg=PT121|volume=Anno 1827, Numero 65 (Agosto)|date=1827|publisher=Cracas|location=Roma|language=Italian|page=1}} {{cite book|editor=Gaetano Moroni |title=Dizionario di erudizione storico-ecclesiastica|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hEbxe8NEAQkC&pg=PA56|volume=Vol. L|year=1851|publisher=Tipografia Emiliana|location=Venezia|language=Italian|pages=56\u201357}} {{cite book|author=Joseph Wolff|title=Travels and Adventures of Joseph Wolff|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EWVCAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA69|volume=Vol. I|year=1860|publisher=Saunders, Otley|location=London|pages=69\u201371}} {{cite book|author=Alan J. Reinerman|title=Austria and the Papacy in the Age of Metternich: Revolution and reaction, 1830-1838|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XclKAQAAMAAJ|year=1989|publisher=Catholic University of America Press|isbn=978-0-8132-0548-9|pages=233\u2013237, 272\u2013274, 396}} {{cite book|author=Giuseppe De Marchi|title=Le nunziature apostoliche dal 1800 al 1956|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cRz3tzdEXGwC&pg=PA75|year=1957|publisher=Ed. di Storia e Letteratura|location=Roma|language=Italian|pages=46, 75, 244}} Ritzler-Sefrin, VII, pp. 61, 360.</ref>\n*Cardinal [[Silvestro Belli]] (1842\u20131844)<ref>Born of a patrician family of Anagni in 1781, Belli completed his studies in philosophy at the seminary of Anagni at the age of fourteen. He completed his theological courses at the age of eighteen, and was named secretary of Bishop Giovanni Devoti. Bishop Tosi made him a Canon of the cathedral Chapter. He taught philosophy in the junior seminary until 1817, and became its Rector. Following the death of his brother Francesco in 1818, he obtained the position of ''Sommista'' at the Congregation of the Propaganda, where he became familiar with the Prefect, Cardinal Cappellari, later [[Pope Gregory XVI]]. In 1823 he was secretary of the extraordinary Papal Commission sent to Holland under Cardinal Nasalli. Under the new pope, [[Pope Leo XII|Leo XII]], he was appointed a ''Beneficiatus'' of the Vatican Basilica, and at the same time became Auditor of Cardinal Nasalli. [[Pope Pius VIII]] named him Privy Chamberlain and ''Guardaroba'' in 1829, then Domestic Prelate (monsignor), and then ''Luogotenente Civile'' in the Vicariate of Rome. Gregory XVI named him Delegate in Benevento, then delegate in Orvieto, and in July 1832 President of the Province of Fermo, where he served for two years. On his return to Rome he was promoted Canon of the Vatican Basilica, and in 1834 was named Substitute Secretary of State for Internal Affairs, where he served for four years. He was appointed Secretary of the Consistorial Congregation in 1836, which made him Secretary of the College of Cardinals as well. In 1839, he was appointed Assessor of the Congregation of the Universal and Roman Inquisition. He was named a cardinal on 14 December 1840, but the fact was not made public until 12 July 1841; he was assigned the [[titular church]] of [[Santa Balbina]]. He was appointed Bishop of Jesi on 24 January 1842, and was consecrated in Rome on 24 February by Cardinal Carlo Pedicini. He died in Jesi on 9 September 1844, after a long illness. {{cite book|author=Vincenzo Sabbatini|title=Societ\u00e0 di Agricoltura Jesina. Annali ed Atti|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pYzrptsDhqcC&pg=PA284|volume=Vol. II|year=1844|location=Jesi|language=Italian|pages=277\u2013284|chapter=Cenno sulla vita del Cardinale Silvestro Belli}}</ref>\n*Cardinal [[Cosimo Corsi]] (1845\u20131853)<ref>Corsi was a native of Florence, son of  Marquis Giuseppe Antonio Corsi and Countess Maddalena della Gherardesca. He held the degree of ''[[Doctor of both laws|Doctor in utroque iure]]'' and theology from the University of Rome, La Sapienza (1818). He was named a cardinal in the Consistory of 24 January 1842, and assigned the [[titular church]] of Saints John and Paul. He was appointed Bishop of Jesi on 20 January 1845. On 19 Dec 1853 Corsi was appointed [[Archbishop of Pisa]]. He was imprisoned for two months, for having refused to celebrate a ''Te Deum'' in honor of the new King of Italy, Vittorio Emanuele II. He died on 7 October 1870. {{cite book|title=Relazione autentica dell'arresto del card. Cosimo Corsi arcivescovo di Pisa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nwuh1FkbA9wC&pg=PP7|year=1860|publisher=Gio. Fassi-Como|location=Genoa|language=Italian}} {{cite book|author=Aldo-Luigi Brogialdi|title=Il buon pastore o il cardinale Cosimo Corsi arcivescovo di Pisa parole dette... ne' funerali solenni celebrati da' cattolici pisani in s. Eufrasia il 12 novembre 1870|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C-4Dwo30bTwC&pg=PA17|year=1870|publisher=Tip.  G. Alisi|location=Pisa|language=Italian}} Mauro Del Corso (1988), ''Un vescovo nella storia: Cosimo Corsi, cardinale di Pisa, la storia di un vescovo'' (Pisa: Pacini 1988). Ritzler-Sefrin, VII, pp. 33, 61.</ref>\n*Cardinal [[Carlo Luigi Morichini]] (23 Jun 1854 \u20131871)<ref>On 24 Nov 1871 Cardinal Morichini was transferred to the diocese of  [[Archbishop of Bologna|Bologna]] by [[Pope Pius IX]].</ref>\n*Rambaldo Magagnini (1872\u20131892)<ref>Rambaldo Magagnini was born in Jesi in 1807. He held the degree of ''[[Doctor of both laws|Doctor in utroque iure]]'' and theology from the University of Rome, La Sapienza. He had previously been Prior of the cathedral Chapter of Jesi, and pro-Vicar-General of the diocese. He was named bishop of Jesi on 6 May 1872. He died on 21 December 1892. {{cite book|title=Roma 6 maggio 1872 provvista di chiese|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rJyxPntcYK8C&pg=PP10|year=1872|location=Rome|language=Italian|page=4}} {{cite book|title=La Gerarchia Cattolica e la Famiglia Pontificia: 1875|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y9mQwe5I5cwC|year=1875|publisher=Monaldi|location=Roma|language=Italian|page=211}}</ref>\n*Aurelio Zonghi (12 Jun 1893 \u2013 9 Jan 1902 Resigned)\n*Giovanni Battista Ricci (9 Jun 1902 \u2013 21 Jul 1906 Appointed, [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Ancona-Osimo|Archbishop of Ancona e Numana]])\n*Giuseppe Gandolfi (1 Dec 1906 \u2013 14 Sep 1927 Died)\n*Goffredo Zaccherini (15 Jun 1928 \u2013 11 May 1934 Resigned)\n*Carlo Falcinelli (6 Sep 1934 \u2013 6 Nov 1952 Resigned)\n*Giovanni Battista Pardini (7 Jan 1953 \u2013 30 Apr 1975 Resigned)\n*Oscar Serfilippi, [[O.F.M. Conv.]] (1 Mar 1978 \u2013 20 Mar 2006 Retired)<ref>Serfilippi was born in Mondolfo in 1929. He was a parish priest between 1958 and 1970. He was elected Minister Provincial of the Province of March of the Conventual Franciscans. On 3 September 1975 he was appointed titular bishop of Massula and Auxiliary Bishop of Ancona-Numana. He was named Auxiliary Bishop of Jesi on 1977, and on 1 March 1978 he became Bishop of Jesi. He died on 20 May 2006, two months after his resignation of the bishopric. ''Find a Grave'', [https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/27651687/oscar-serfilippi \"Rev. Oscar Serfilippi\"]; retrieved: 9 March 2019.</ref>\n*Gerardo Rocconi (20 Mar 2006 \u2013 present)<ref>Rocconi was born at Corinaldo (Ancona) in 1949. From 1968 to 1973 he studied philosophy and theology  at the regional seminary in Fano and Ancona. He was ordained a priest for the diocese of Senigallia in 1973, where, from 1973 to 1986 he was Vice-Rector and then Rector of the seminary of Senigallia. From 1985 to 1997 he was a parish priest in Chiaravalle, and from 1992 to 1997 he was Vicar General of the diocese of Senigallia. He was named Bishop of Jesi by [[Pope Benedict XVI]] on 20 March 2006, and consecrated a bishop on 29 April 2006. CV: Diocesi di Jesi, [http://www.jesi.chiesacattolica.it/vescovo.html \"Il vescovo: S.E. Mons. Gerardo Rocconi\"]; retrieved: 28 February 2019. {{in lang|it}}</ref>\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*Diocesi di Jesi, [http://www.jesi.chiesacattolica.it/diocesi.html ''Guida diocesana 2018''] (Press the gray bar entitled \"Scarica la Guida Diocesana\"); retrieved: 5 March 2019.\n\n==Bibliography==\n===Reference works for bishops===\n*{{cite book|last=Gams|first=Pius Bonifatius |title=Series episcoporum Ecclesiae catholicae: quotquot innotuerunt a beato Petro apostolo|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=os9DAQAAMAAJ|year=1873|publisher=Typis et Sumptibus Georgii Josephi Manz|location=Ratisbon|language=Latin}} pp.&nbsp;700-701.\n \n*{{cite book|last1=Eubel|first1=Conradus (ed.)|last2=Gulik|first2=Guilelmus|title=Hierarchia catholica|volume= Tomus 3|date=1923|publisher=Libreria Regensbergiana|language=Latin|location=M\u00fcnster|edition=second|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol02eubeuoft}} \n*{{cite book|last1=Gauchat|first1=Patritius (Patrice)|title=Hierarchia catholica|volume=Tomus IV (1592-1667)|date=1935|publisher=Libraria Regensbergiana|location=M\u00fcnster|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol04eubeuoft}} \n*{{cite book|last1=Ritzler|first1=Remigius|last2=Sefrin|first2=Pirminus|title=Hierarchia catholica medii et recentis aevi|volume=Tomus V (1667-1730)|date=1952|publisher=Messagero di S. Antonio|location=Patavii|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol05eubeuoft}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Ritzler|first1=Remigius|last2=Sefrin|first2=Pirminus|title=Hierarchia catholica medii et recentis aevi|volume=Tomus VI (1730-1799)|date=1958|publisher=Messagero di S. Antonio|location=Patavii|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol06eubeuoft}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Ritzler|first1=Remigius|last2=Sefrin|first2=Pirminus|title=Hierarchia Catholica medii et recentioris aevi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pgyItwAACAAJ|volume=Volume VII (1800\u20131846)|year=1968|publisher=Libreria Regensburgiana|location=Monasterii|language=Latin}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Remigius Ritzler|author2=Pirminus Sefrin|title=Hierarchia catholica Medii et recentioris aevi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5oXUjwEACAAJ|year=1978|volume=Volume VIII (1846\u20131903)|publisher=Il Messaggero di S. Antonio|language=Latin}}\n*{{cite book|last= Pi\u0119ta|first=Zenon|title=Hierarchia catholica medii et recentioris aevi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QXuJQwAACAAJ|volume=Volume IX (1903\u20131922)|year=2002|publisher=Messagero di San Antonio|location=Padua|language=Latin|isbn=978-88-250-1000-8}}\n\n===Studies===\n*{{cite book|last=Baldassini|first=Girolamo|title=Memorie istoriche dell'antichissima e regia citt\u00e0 di Jesi|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_7lAc3Ka1T9MC|year=1765|publisher=Pietropaolo Bonelli|location=Jesi|language=Italian|pages=361\u2013382}}\n*{{cite book|last=Cappelletti|first=Giuseppe|title=Le chiese d'Italia della loro origine sino ai nostri giorni|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vtICAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA195|volume=Volume settimo|year=1848|publisher=G. Antonelli|location=Venezia|language=Italian|pages=271\u2013320}}\n*Lanzoni, Francesco (1927). ''[https://archive.org/stream/MN5017ucmf_0#page/n281/mode/2up Le diocesi d'Italia dalle origini al principio del secolo VII (an. 604)]''. Faenza: F. Lega, pp.&nbsp;490-492. {{in lang|it}}\n*Mezzadri, L; Tagliaferri, M; Guerriero, E. (eds) (2008), ''Le diocesi d'Italia'' Volume III (Torino, San Paolo edizioni, 2008). {{in lang|it}}\n*{{cite book|last=Stefani|first=G.|title=Dizionario corografico dello Stato Pontificio|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QdJoAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA575|year=1856|publisher=Presso gli Stabilimenti di Civelli G. e C.|location=Milano e Verona|language=Italian|pages=506\u2013515}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Ughelli|first1=Ferdinando|last2=Coleti|first2=Niccol\u00f2|title=Italia sacra, sive De Episcopis Italiae|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zTkOnHgYhFgC|volume=Tomus primus|edition=secunda|year=1717|publisher=apud Sebastianum Coleti|location=Venice|language=Latin|pages=279-287}}\n\n====Acknowledgment====\n::{